{
  "id": "how-it-works-outline",
  "name": "IdiamPro - How it works",
  "rootNodeId": "root",
  "nodes": {
    "root": {
      "id": "root",
      "name": "IdiamPro - How it works",
      "content": "<p><strong>A Plain-Language Guide to How IdiamPro Works</strong></p><p>This outline explains how IdiamPro is built and how all its pieces work together. Written for anyone curious about the app's inner workings, no programming experience needed.</p><p><em>Last updated: 2/7/26</em></p>",
      "type": "root",
      "parentId": null,
      "childrenIds": [
        "f79853c1-2d2b-43f9-aba6-fa9c2ffc718e",
        "overview",
        "platforms",
        "data-storage",
        "main-screen",
        "outline-tree",
        "content-editor",
        "ai-features",
        "file-management",
        "keyboard-mouse",
        "under-the-hood",
        "second-brain-8232afad",
        "launch-metrics",
        "48b45703-8432-4467-a3e8-96caca3d777b",
        "onboarding-emails-2026-06-05",
        "web-payment-stripe-revenuecat-2026-06-05",
        "auth-wall-section-b7c0ebd8",
        "tech-stack-platform-strategy-2026-06-06",
        "5b35f388-dd86-4459-aa4c-4c15b6e8522e",
        "beta-feedback-form-2026-06-10",
        "multimedia-ai-2026-06-11",
        "email-system-plain-english-2026-06-11",
        "operations-link-2026-06-11"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "overview": {
      "id": "overview",
      "name": "What is IdiamPro?",
      "content": "<p>IdiamPro is an <strong>outlining application</strong> — a tool for organizing your thoughts, notes, research, and projects in a tree-like structure.</p><p>Think of it like a folder system on your computer, but instead of files and folders, you have <strong>nodes</strong> (individual pieces of information) that can contain text, images, videos, and more. Each node can have child nodes underneath it, creating a hierarchy that helps you see the big picture while also being able to dive into details.</p><p><strong>What makes it special:</strong></p><ul><li>AI-powered features that can generate outlines, summarize content, and help with research</li><li>Works on Mac, iOS, and the web today, with Windows, Linux, and Android in the cross-platform plan</li><li>All your data stays on your computer — you own your information</li><li>Rich content support including images, videos, diagrams, and embedded documents</li></ul>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "1"
    },
    "platforms": {
      "id": "platforms",
      "name": "Where Can You Use It?",
      "content": "<p>IdiamPro runs on multiple platforms, meaning you can use it in different ways depending on what device you're on.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [
        "platform-desktop",
        "platform-web",
        "platform-ios"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "2"
    },
    "platform-desktop": {
      "id": "platform-desktop",
      "name": "Desktop App (Mac)",
      "content": "<p>The main way to use IdiamPro is as a <strong>desktop application</strong> on your Mac. This version has all the features and runs using a technology called <strong>Electron</strong>.</p><p><strong>What is Electron?</strong> It's a way to turn web pages into desktop apps. Under the hood, IdiamPro is built like a website, but Electron wraps it up so it looks and feels like a regular Mac app. This means:</p><ul><li>It can read and write files on your computer</li><li>It can create automatic backups</li><li>It works offline (no internet needed)</li><li>You get a dock icon and can use keyboard shortcuts like any other app</li></ul><p>Your outline files are stored in <code>~/Documents/IDM Outlines/</code> — that's a folder in your Documents called \"IDM Outlines.\"</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "platforms",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "2.1"
    },
    "platform-web": {
      "id": "platform-web",
      "name": "Web Browser Version",
      "content": "<p>You can also use IdiamPro in a web browser by going to the website. This version uses something called the <strong>File System Access API</strong> — a modern browser feature that lets websites (with your permission) read and write files on your computer.</p><p><strong>How it works:</strong></p><ol><li>You visit the IdiamPro website</li><li>The browser asks permission to access a folder</li><li>You pick your IDM Outlines folder</li><li>Now the website can save your work just like the desktop app</li></ol><p><strong>Limitations:</strong> If your browser doesn't support this feature, your outlines will be saved in the browser's local storage instead (a small space the browser sets aside for websites to store data). This works but isn't as reliable as real files.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "platforms",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "2.2"
    },
    "platform-ios": {
      "id": "platform-ios",
      "name": "iOS App (iPhone/iPad)",
      "content": "<p>IdiamPro also runs on iPhones and iPads using a technology called <strong>Capacitor</strong>.</p><p><strong>What is Capacitor?</strong> It's a bridge that lets web apps (like IdiamPro) access phone features like the camera, file storage, and touch gestures. The app looks and works like a native iOS app, but inside it's running the same code as the web version.</p><p><strong>iOS-specific features:</strong></p><ul><li>Swipe gestures to indent/outdent nodes</li><li>Long-press for context menus (like right-click on a Mac)</li><li>Works with iOS keyboard shortcuts if you have an external keyboard</li></ul>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "platforms",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "2.3"
    },
    "data-storage": {
      "id": "data-storage",
      "name": "How Your Data is Stored",
      "content": "<p>Understanding where your information lives helps you feel confident that your work is safe.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [
        "storage-files",
        "storage-backups",
        "howitworks-backup-restore-2026-06-10",
        "howitworks-derivative-outlines-2026-06-10",
        "storage-lazy"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "3"
    },
    "storage-files": {
      "id": "storage-files",
      "name": "Outline Files (.idm)",
      "content": "<p>Each outline you create becomes a single file with the extension <code>.idm</code> (which stands for IdiamPro Data Model). These files are stored in:</p><p><code>~/Documents/IDM Outlines/</code></p><p><strong>Inside the file:</strong> It's actually just a text file in a format called <strong>JSON</strong> (JavaScript Object Notation). If you opened it in a text editor, you'd see something like:</p><pre><code>{\n  \"id\": \"abc123\",\n  \"name\": \"My Outline\",\n  \"nodes\": {\n    \"node1\": {\n      \"name\": \"First item\",\n      \"content\": \"Some text here...\"\n    }\n  }\n}</code></pre><p>This human-readable format means your data isn't locked away — you could technically edit it by hand if you wanted to (though that's not recommended!).</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "data-storage",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "3.1"
    },
    "storage-backups": {
      "id": "storage-backups",
      "name": "Automatic Backups",
      "content": "<p>The desktop app automatically creates backup copies of your outlines to protect against accidents.</p><p><strong>Where are they?</strong></p><p><code>~/Documents/IDM Outlines/backups/</code></p><p><strong>How it works:</strong></p><ul><li>Every time you make changes, the app considers creating a backup</li><li>It waits at least 5 minutes between backups (so you don't get hundreds of copies)</li><li>Backup files are named with timestamps like <code>MyOutline_backup_2026-02-07T14-30-00.idm</code></li><li>The app keeps the 10 most recent backups for each outline and deletes older ones</li></ul><p><strong>Recovery:</strong> If something goes wrong, you can find your backup files in that folder and rename one to remove the \"_backup\" part to restore it.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "data-storage",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "3.2"
    },
    "storage-lazy": {
      "id": "storage-lazy",
      "name": "Smart Loading for Large Outlines",
      "content": "<p>Some outlines can get very large — imagine an outline with 50,000 nodes and 50 megabytes of content. Loading all of that every time you open the app would be slow.</p><p><strong>The solution: Lazy Loading</strong></p><p>When the app starts, it looks at each outline file:</p><ul><li><strong>Small files (under 1 MB):</strong> Loaded completely right away</li><li><strong>Large files (over 1 MB):</strong> Only the basic info is loaded (name, number of nodes). The full content waits until you actually click on that outline.</li></ul><p>You'll see a message like \"Loading 5,000 nodes...\" when you first open a large outline. After that, it stays in memory and works fast.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "data-storage",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "3.3"
    },
    "main-screen": {
      "id": "main-screen",
      "name": "The Main Screen Layout",
      "content": "<p>When you open IdiamPro, you see a screen divided into sections. Each section has a specific job.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [
        "screen-sidebar",
        "screen-outline",
        "screen-content"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "4"
    },
    "screen-sidebar": {
      "id": "screen-sidebar",
      "name": "The Sidebar (Left Edge)",
      "content": "<p>On the far left is a narrow sidebar showing all your outlines as a list. This is handled by a part of the app called the <strong>Sidebar Pane</strong>.</p><p><strong>What you can do here (desktop):</strong></p><ul><li>Click an outline name to switch to it</li><li>Right-click for options like rename, duplicate, or delete</li><li>Click the + button to create a new outline</li><li>Search outlines by name</li><li>Cmd/Ctrl-click or Shift-click to select multiple outlines for bulk delete</li></ul><p><strong>On mobile (iPhone / touch):</strong> The sidebar appears as a bottom sheet, a separate component called the <strong>Mobile Sidebar Sheet</strong>. Tap rows have larger tap targets (~48px) and always show a ⋯ menu on the right with Rename and Delete. <strong>Long-press</strong> an outline (~half a second) to enter multi-select mode — a top bar appears showing how many are selected, with Cancel and Delete buttons. While in select mode, taps toggle selection instead of opening the outline. Renaming an outline replaces its name with an inline input field where Enter saves and Escape cancels.</p><p>The sidebar only shows outline names — it's like looking at a bookshelf where you only see the spines of the books.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "main-screen",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "4.1"
    },
    "screen-outline": {
      "id": "screen-outline",
      "name": "The Outline Tree (Left Panel)",
      "content": "<p>Next to the sidebar is the <strong>Outline Pane</strong> — a tree view showing all the nodes in your current outline.</p><p><strong>What you see:</strong></p><ul><li>Nodes arranged in a hierarchy (parents above, children indented below)</li><li>Little triangle icons to expand/collapse sections</li><li>Icons showing what type each node is (document, chapter, image, etc.)</li><li>Numbers like \"1.2.3\" showing each node's position</li></ul><p><strong>The toolbar at the top</strong> has buttons for:</p><ul><li>Creating new nodes</li><li><strong>Import</strong> (down-arrow book) — menu with Research & Import, Import Outline, Restore All Outlines</li><li><strong>Export</strong> (up-arrow book) — menu with Share Branch as…, Export Current Outline, Backup All Outlines</li><li><strong>Show or hide all nodes</strong> (bidirectional double-chevron) — one button that opens a dropdown with Expand all and Collapse all. Replaces the previous pair of side-by-side single-direction chevron buttons. Keyboard shortcuts Cmd+E and Cmd+Shift+E still work directly without opening the menu.</li><li>AI features (the sparkle icon)</li><li>Search (magnifying glass)</li></ul>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "main-screen",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "4.2"
    },
    "screen-content": {
      "id": "screen-content",
      "name": "The Content Editor (Right Panel)",
      "content": "<p>The largest area is the <strong>Content Pane</strong> — where you actually read and write content for the selected node.</p><p><strong>What you see:</strong></p><ul><li>The node's name at the top (editable)</li><li>A rich text editor below for the node's content</li><li>A formatting toolbar for bold, italic, lists, headings, etc.</li><li>Buttons for inserting special content (images, code blocks, diagrams)</li></ul><p>The editor is powered by something called <strong>TipTap</strong>, which is like a more powerful version of what you'd find in email or word processors. It understands formatting, can embed images and videos, and saves everything as HTML (the same code used for web pages).</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "main-screen",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "4.3"
    },
    "outline-tree": {
      "id": "outline-tree",
      "name": "How the Outline Tree Works",
      "content": "<p>The heart of IdiamPro is its tree structure. Understanding how it works helps you organize information effectively.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [
        "tree-nodes",
        "tree-types",
        "tree-operations",
        "search-filters"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "5"
    },
    "tree-nodes": {
      "id": "tree-nodes",
      "name": "Nodes: The Building Blocks",
      "content": "<p>Everything in an outline is a <strong>node</strong>. Each node has:</p><p><strong>Required properties:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>ID</strong> — A unique identifier (like a social security number for nodes)</li><li><strong>Name</strong> — The title you see in the tree (keep it short, 2-6 words works best)</li><li><strong>Content</strong> — The actual text and media inside the node</li><li><strong>Type</strong> — What kind of node it is (document, chapter, image, etc.)</li><li><strong>Parent ID</strong> — Which node this one belongs under (or \"null\" for the root)</li><li><strong>Children IDs</strong> — A list of nodes that belong under this one</li></ul><p><strong>Optional properties:</strong></p><ul><li>Tags for organization</li><li>Colors for visual grouping</li><li>Due dates for tasks</li><li>Collapse state (expanded or collapsed)</li></ul>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "outline-tree",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "5.1"
    },
    "tree-types": {
      "id": "tree-types",
      "name": "Node Types",
      "content": "<p>Each node has a type that affects its icon and sometimes its behavior:</p><p><strong>Basic types:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Root</strong> — The top-level node (every outline has exactly one)</li><li><strong>Chapter</strong> — A section with children (like a folder)</li><li><strong>Document</strong> — A content node (like a file)</li><li><strong>Note</strong> — A quick note or idea</li><li><strong>Task</strong> — Something to do (can be marked complete)</li></ul><p><strong>Media types:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Image</strong> — Contains a picture</li><li><strong>Video</strong> — Contains or links to video</li><li><strong>Audio</strong> — Contains or links to audio</li><li><strong>PDF</strong> — Links to a PDF document</li><li><strong>YouTube</strong> — Embeds a YouTube video</li></ul><p><strong>Special types:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Code</strong> — For programming code with syntax highlighting</li><li><strong>Quote</strong> — A quotation</li><li><strong>Link</strong> — Points to a website</li><li><strong>Canvas</strong> — A drawing area</li><li><strong>Spreadsheet</strong> — A mini Excel-like grid</li></ul>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "outline-tree",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "5.2"
    },
    "tree-operations": {
      "id": "tree-operations",
      "name": "Moving and Organizing Nodes",
      "content": "<p>The tree isn't static — you can reorganize it freely.</p><p><strong>Basic operations:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Create</strong> — Press Enter to add a sibling node below the current one</li><li><strong>Delete</strong> — Removes a node and all its children</li><li><strong>Indent (Tab)</strong> — Moves a node to become a child of the node above it</li><li><strong>Outdent (Shift+Tab)</strong> — Moves a node up a level</li></ul><p><strong>Drag and Drop:</strong></p><p>You can drag nodes to rearrange them. When you drag over a target node:</p><ul><li>Dropping on the <strong>top third</strong> places it before that node</li><li>Dropping on the <strong>middle</strong> makes it a child of that node</li><li>Dropping on the <strong>bottom third</strong> places it after that node</li></ul><p><strong>Copy/Cut/Paste:</strong></p><p>Works like regular copy/paste, but copies entire branches (a node and all its children).</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "outline-tree",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "5.3"
    },
    "content-editor": {
      "id": "content-editor",
      "name": "The Content Editor",
      "content": "<p>The content editor is where you write and format the actual content of each node.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [
        "editor-tiptap",
        "editor-formatting",
        "editor-embeds"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "6"
    },
    "editor-tiptap": {
      "id": "editor-tiptap",
      "name": "TipTap: The Editor Engine",
      "content": "<p>IdiamPro's content editor is built on <strong>TipTap</strong>, an open-source rich text editor.</p><p><strong>What makes it good:</strong></p><ul><li>Works like a normal word processor — just type and format</li><li>Understands markdown shortcuts (type ** for bold, # for headings)</li><li>Can embed complex content like diagrams and videos</li><li>Undo/redo with Cmd+Z</li></ul><p><strong>How content is saved:</strong></p><p>Everything you type is converted to HTML (HyperText Markup Language — the code that makes web pages). For example:</p><ul><li>Bold text becomes <code>&lt;strong&gt;bold text&lt;/strong&gt;</code></li><li>A paragraph becomes <code>&lt;p&gt;Your paragraph&lt;/p&gt;</code></li><li>A list becomes <code>&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;item&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;</code></li></ul><p>You don't need to know HTML — the editor handles this automatically.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "content-editor",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "6.1"
    },
    "editor-formatting": {
      "id": "editor-formatting",
      "name": "Formatting Options",
      "content": "<p>The toolbar provides buttons for all common formatting:</p><p><strong>Text formatting:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Bold</strong> (Cmd+B)</li><li><em>Italic</em> (Cmd+I)</li><li><u>Underline</u> (Cmd+U)</li><li><s>Strikethrough</s></li><li><code>Code</code> (inline)</li></ul><p><strong>Block formatting:</strong></p><ul><li>Headings (H1 through H6)</li><li>Bullet lists</li><li>Numbered lists</li><li>Checklists (todo items)</li><li>Block quotes</li><li>Code blocks (for programming code)</li><li>Horizontal lines</li></ul><p><strong>Special content:</strong></p><ul><li>Links (Cmd+K)</li><li>Images (paste or upload)</li><li>Mermaid diagrams (for flowcharts)</li><li>Embedded videos and audio</li></ul><p><strong>Touch-accessible toolbar (iPhone, iPad, and desktop):</strong></p><p>The content pane toolbar includes one-tap buttons for the most common editor actions, so iPhone users don't have to rely on right-click menus:</p><ul><li><strong>Undo</strong> and <strong>Redo</strong> buttons at the left end of the toolbar</li><li><strong>Bullet List</strong>, <strong>Numbered List</strong>, and <strong>Checklist</strong> buttons (each highlights when the current block is that list type)</li></ul><p><strong>Floating formatting toolbar (BubbleMenu):</strong></p><p>When you select any text in the editor, a small floating menu pops up just above the selection with Bold, Italic, Strikethrough, Inline Code, and Heading 1/2/3 buttons. Buttons highlight to show which formatting is already applied. This is built on TipTap's BubbleMenu (using Floating UI for positioning) and works equally well with a mouse, trackpad, or touch.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "content-editor",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "6.2"
    },
    "editor-embeds": {
      "id": "editor-embeds",
      "name": "Embedded Content",
      "content": "<p>You can embed various types of content directly into your nodes:</p><p><strong>Images:</strong></p><ul><li>Paste from clipboard</li><li>Drag and drop files</li><li>Upload from your computer</li><li>Images are stored inside the outline file (as data URLs)</li></ul><p><strong>Videos and Audio:</strong></p><ul><li>YouTube videos — paste a YouTube link</li><li>Local video/audio files — upload or link</li><li>Plays right in the editor</li></ul><p><strong>Documents:</strong></p><ul><li>Google Docs, Sheets, Slides — embedded as iframes</li><li>PDFs — linked or extracted as text</li></ul><p><strong>Diagrams:</strong></p><ul><li>Mermaid — write simple code that turns into flowcharts</li><li>Canvas — freehand drawing with the Excalidraw tool</li></ul>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "content-editor",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "6.3"
    },
    "ai-features": {
      "id": "ai-features",
      "name": "AI-Powered Features",
      "content": "<p>IdiamPro includes artificial intelligence features that can help you create, research, and organize content.</p><p><strong>Reformat with AI (added 2026-06-05):</strong> a single-shot transform that takes one node's content (or just the selected text inside the editor) plus a plain-language instruction (\"turn into a bulleted list\", \"make each line a heading\", \"convert to clean prose\") and returns reformatted HTML. Different shape from Refresh from Web and Translate: it does NOT use the branch transform engine — it's one HTML fragment in, one HTML fragment out via a server action (reformatContentAction → reformatContent flow). The Reformat dialog runs through three phases (input → running → preview) and only commits via the parent's onApply callback. Reachable from Smart Tools menu, Cmd+K command palette, editor right-click, and the violet wand button in the floating formatting toolbar (bubble menu) when text is selected. Tier-gated through useAIUsageGate with feature key 'reformat'; not Pro-only.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [
        "ai-generation",
        "ai-research",
        "ai-chat",
        "ai-podcast",
        "ai-livebooks",
        "ai-providers",
        "ai-consent-system",
        "discovery-hints-2026-06-05"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "7"
    },
    "ai-generation": {
      "id": "ai-generation",
      "name": "Outline Generation",
      "content": "<p>Give the AI a topic, and it will create a structured outline for you.</p><p><strong>How to use it:</strong></p><ol><li>Click the sparkle icon (AI menu)</li><li>Choose \"Generate Outline\"</li><li>Type a topic like \"History of the Roman Empire\"</li><li>The AI creates a multi-level outline with chapters and sections</li></ol><p><strong>What happens behind the scenes:</strong></p><p>Your topic is sent to an AI service (Google's Gemini by default) with instructions to create an educational outline. The AI returns a structured list that IdiamPro converts into nodes.</p><p><strong>Content expansion:</strong></p><p>Select any node and ask the AI to \"expand\" it — adding more detail and child nodes based on the context.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ai-features",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "7.1"
    },
    "ai-research": {
      "id": "ai-research",
      "name": "Research & Import",
      "content": "<p>The Research & Import feature lets you add external sources (YouTube videos, web pages, PDFs) and have the AI synthesize them into your outline.</p><p><strong>How it works:</strong></p><ol><li>Click the book icon (Research & Import)</li><li>Add one or more sources — paste URLs or upload files</li><li>Choose how to merge them: synthesize together, keep separate, or create an architecture</li><li>The AI extracts content from each source and creates new nodes</li><li>Preview the changes before applying them</li></ol><p><strong>Source types supported:</strong></p><ul><li>YouTube videos — transcribes the audio</li><li>Web pages — extracts the main content</li><li>PDFs — reads the text</li><li>Images — uses OCR to read text in pictures</li><li>Audio/video files — transcribes speech</li></ul><p><strong>Unmerge:</strong> If you don't like the result, click Unmerge to restore your outline to its previous state.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ai-features",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "7.2"
    },
    "ai-chat": {
      "id": "ai-chat",
      "name": "Knowledge Chat",
      "content": "<p>Ask questions about your outlines and get AI-powered answers.</p><p><strong>How to use it:</strong></p><ol><li>Click the brain icon</li><li>Choose \"Current Outline\" or \"All Outlines\"</li><li>Type a question like \"What are the main themes in my research?\"</li><li>The AI reads through your content and answers</li></ol><p><strong>Behind the scenes:</strong></p><p>The app creates a \"knowledge base\" — a combined text file of all your outline content. When you ask a question, this context is sent to the AI along with your question, so it can give answers based on YOUR information, not just general knowledge.</p><p><strong>Help Chat:</strong> A separate chat feature answers questions about how to use IdiamPro itself (not your content).</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ai-features",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "7.3"
    },
    "ai-podcast": {
      "id": "ai-podcast",
      "name": "Podcast Generation",
      "content": "<p>Turn any node (and its children) into an audio podcast.</p><p><strong>How it works:</strong></p><ol><li>Right-click a node and choose \"Generate Podcast\"</li><li>Choose a style: two hosts discussing, a narrator, an interview, or a debate</li><li>Pick voices for each speaker</li><li>Select length: brief (2-3 min), standard (5-8 min), or detailed (10-15 min)</li><li>The AI writes a script and then reads it aloud</li></ol><p><strong>The process:</strong></p><ol><li>AI reads your outline content</li><li>AI writes a dialogue/script in your chosen style</li><li>Text-to-speech converts each line to audio</li><li>Audio clips are combined into one file</li><li>You can preview and save as MP3</li></ol>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ai-features",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "7.4"
    },
    "ai-providers": {
      "id": "ai-providers",
      "name": "AI Service Providers",
      "content": "<p>IdiamPro can use different AI services depending on your preferences:</p><p><strong>Google Gemini (Default):</strong></p><ul><li>Fast and capable</li><li>Requires internet connection</li><li>Uses Google's servers</li></ul><p><strong>Ollama with Gemma 4 (Local):</strong></p><ul><li>Runs on your own computer</li><li>No data sent to external servers</li><li>Requires installing Ollama software separately (v0.20+)</li><li>Default model: Gemma 4 E4B (multimodal, ~4GB RAM) — can process images locally</li><li>Auto-selects best variant based on system memory: e2b (1.5GB), e4b (4GB), 26b MoE (16GB+), 31b dense (24GB+)</li><li>Falls back to llama3.2 for low-memory systems</li><li>More private; speed depends on hardware</li></ul><p><strong>OpenAI:</strong></p><ul><li>Used for image generation (DALL-E)</li><li>Used for podcast voices (text-to-speech)</li></ul><p>You can switch between providers in Settings. The app will try local AI first and fall back to cloud services if needed.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ai-features",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "7.5"
    },
    "file-management": {
      "id": "file-management",
      "name": "File Management",
      "content": "<p>How IdiamPro handles creating, saving, and protecting your files.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [
        "files-saving",
        "files-import-export",
        "files-pending"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "8"
    },
    "files-saving": {
      "id": "files-saving",
      "name": "Auto-Save",
      "content": "<p>IdiamPro automatically saves your work — you never have to press Cmd+S.</p><p><strong>How it works:</strong></p><ol><li>When you make a change, the outline is marked as \"dirty\" (needs saving)</li><li>The app waits 2 seconds to see if you make more changes</li><li>After 2 seconds of no changes, it saves</li><li>The dirty flag is cleared</li></ol><p>This \"debouncing\" prevents the app from saving after every keystroke, which would be inefficient. Instead, it waits for a pause in your activity.</p><p><strong>What gets saved:</strong></p><ul><li>Only outlines you've actually changed (the \"dirty\" ones)</li><li>The entire outline as a single .idm file</li><li>A backup copy (every 5 minutes)</li></ul>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "file-management",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "8.1"
    },
    "files-import-export": {
      "id": "files-import-export",
      "name": "Import and Export",
      "content": "<p>Import and Export live in the top toolbar as two dedicated icon buttons: a <strong>BookDown</strong> icon (Import) and a <strong>BookUp</strong> icon (Export). Each opens a small menu.</p><p><strong>Import menu:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Research & Import</strong> — pull in multiple external sources (YouTube, PDFs, web pages, audio, etc.) and let AI synthesize them into the current outline.</li><li><strong>Import Outline</strong> — bring in a single outline file (.idm, .json, .md, .txt, .opml). Drag-and-drop or browse.</li><li><strong>Link to Outline…</strong> — insert a cross-outline link node that points at another outline in your library.</li><li><strong>Restore All Outlines</strong> — re-load any outlines from the storage folder back into the sidebar.</li><li><strong>Refresh from Web</strong> — moved here 2026-06-06 from the Smart Tools (sparkles) menu. It brings external web content INTO existing nodes, so it sits naturally with the other import actions. Disabled until a node is selected.</li></ul><p><strong>Export menu:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Share Branch as…</strong> — exports just the currently-selected node and everything under it, in any supported format (PDF, Markdown, HTML, Website, Podcast, OPML, Obsidian, CSV, JSON Tree, etc.). Disabled when no node is selected. The same action is also available by right-clicking any node — the toolbar button is just a discoverable second surface.</li><li><strong>Export Current Outline</strong> — exports the whole active outline.</li><li><strong>Backup All Outlines</strong> — saves every outline to disk in one shot.</li></ul><p><strong>Coming soon (v1.1):</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Video / YouTube export</strong> — Generate a fully-narrated, publishable video straight from any outline. Outline becomes the script, AI narrates it, slides render automatically, and the result is a YouTube-ready MP4. Pick a target length, hit Generate. Set as the customer expectation now even though the code lands in v1.1; the full plan lives in the Bootstrap Plan outline (chapter 17). Beta testers get early access.</li></ul><p>Why two buttons instead of one wrench: Import and Export are the most common file-level actions a user reaches for, so they deserve their own top-level toolbar icons rather than being hidden three layers deep in an admin menu.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "file-management",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "8.2"
    },
    "files-pending": {
      "id": "files-pending",
      "name": "Pending Imports",
      "content": "<p>When you import content from external sources, IdiamPro uses a \"pending\" system to protect your data.</p><p><strong>How it works:</strong></p><ol><li>The import is saved to a special <code>.pending</code> folder</li><li>A dialog shows you what will be added</li><li>You review and click \"Apply\" to merge it in</li><li>The pending file is deleted</li></ol><p><strong>Why this matters:</strong></p><p>If the app crashes during an import, or you close it before finishing, the pending import is still there when you restart. Nothing is lost.</p><p>Look for the \"Pending Imports\" notification when you open the app — it will remind you if there are unfinished imports.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "file-management",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "8.3"
    },
    "keyboard-mouse": {
      "id": "keyboard-mouse",
      "name": "Keyboard Shortcuts and Gestures",
      "content": "<p>IdiamPro is designed to be fast for keyboard users while still being fully usable with a mouse or touch.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [
        "kb-desktop",
        "kb-ios",
        "kb-command-palette"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "9"
    },
    "kb-desktop": {
      "id": "kb-desktop",
      "name": "Desktop Keyboard Shortcuts",
      "content": "<p><strong>Navigation:</strong></p><ul><li>↑/↓ — Move between nodes</li><li>←/→ — Collapse/expand node</li><li>Cmd+/ — Toggle collapse</li></ul><p><strong>Editing:</strong></p><ul><li>Enter — Create new sibling node</li><li>Tab — Indent (make child of previous)</li><li>Shift+Tab — Outdent (move up a level)</li><li>Cmd+D — Duplicate node</li><li>Delete — Delete node</li></ul><p><strong>Text formatting:</strong></p><ul><li>Cmd+B — Bold</li><li>Cmd+I — Italic</li><li>Cmd+U — Underline</li><li>Cmd+K — Insert link</li></ul><p><strong>App:</strong></p><ul><li>Cmd+N — New outline</li><li>Cmd+, — Settings</li><li>Cmd+K — Command palette</li><li>Ctrl+F — Search</li><li>Cmd+Shift+F — Focus mode</li></ul>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "keyboard-mouse",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "9.1"
    },
    "kb-ios": {
      "id": "kb-ios",
      "name": "iOS Touch Gestures",
      "content": "<p>On iPhone and iPad, touch gestures replace many keyboard shortcuts:</p><p><strong>Selection:</strong></p><ul><li>Tap — Select a node</li><li>Tap again (on selected node) — Edit the name</li><li>Double-tap — Create sibling node</li><li>Long-press (still finger, ~500ms) — Enter multi-select mode; that node becomes the first selection. Then plain taps on other nodes toggle them in or out of the selection. A small haptic buzz fires on entry where supported.</li></ul><p><strong>Organization:</strong></p><ul><li>Swipe right — Indent</li><li>Swipe left — Outdent</li><li>Long-press + drag — Move node (any finger movement during the long-press defers to drag instead of multi-select)</li></ul><p><strong>Menus:</strong></p><ul><li>Long-press — The system may also show its context menu; right-click on desktop opens the same menu</li><li>The context menu has been trimmed to essentials. Type, Color, and Tags now live behind a single 'Properties...' item at the bottom — one dialog instead of three submenus.</li></ul><p><strong>Tap targets:</strong> The chevron (expand/collapse) and task checkbox use a 32px hit area on every node so they're easy to tap on touch screens.</p><p><strong>Note:</strong> Some gestures are reserved by iOS (like pinch to zoom or edge swipes for navigation). IdiamPro avoids conflicting with these system gestures. The pin/star button has been removed — nodes no longer show a star icon.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "keyboard-mouse",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "9.2"
    },
    "kb-command-palette": {
      "id": "kb-command-palette",
      "name": "The Command Palette",
      "content": "<p>Press <strong>Cmd+K</strong> to open the command palette — a quick way to access any feature.</p><p><strong>How to use it:</strong></p><ol><li>Press Cmd+K</li><li>Start typing what you want to do</li><li>Select from the filtered list</li><li>Press Enter to execute</li></ol><p><strong>What you can do:</strong></p><ul><li>Create new outlines</li><li>Switch between outlines</li><li>Change node types</li><li>Access settings</li><li>Run AI features</li><li>And more...</li></ul><p>The command palette is inspired by tools like VS Code and Spotlight — it's faster than clicking through menus once you learn to use it.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "keyboard-mouse",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "9.3"
    },
    "under-the-hood": {
      "id": "under-the-hood",
      "name": "Under the Hood",
      "content": "<p>For the curious: a peek at the technologies that make IdiamPro work.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [
        "tech-stack",
        "tech-components",
        "tech-data-flow",
        "external-mod-detection",
        "tier-enforcement"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "10"
    },
    "tech-stack": {
      "id": "tech-stack",
      "name": "The Technology Stack",
      "content": "<p><strong>Frontend (What you see):</strong></p><ul><li><strong>React</strong> — A popular library for building user interfaces, made by Facebook</li><li><strong>Next.js</strong> — A framework that adds features like server-side rendering to React</li><li><strong>TypeScript</strong> — JavaScript with added type safety (catches errors before they happen)</li><li><strong>Tailwind CSS</strong> — A styling system for making things look good</li><li><strong>Radix UI</strong> — Pre-built accessible components (buttons, dialogs, etc.)</li></ul><p><strong>Desktop (Electron):</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Electron</strong> — Wraps web pages in a desktop app shell</li><li><strong>Node.js</strong> — JavaScript that runs on your computer (not in a browser)</li></ul><p><strong>Mobile (iOS):</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Capacitor</strong> — Bridges web apps to native iOS features</li></ul><p><strong>AI:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Genkit</strong> — Google's toolkit for building AI features</li><li><strong>Google Gemini</strong> — The AI model that generates text</li><li><strong>OpenAI</strong> — For images and text-to-speech</li></ul>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "under-the-hood",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "10.1"
    },
    "tech-components": {
      "id": "tech-components",
      "name": "How Components Work",
      "content": "<p>IdiamPro is built from about 80 separate <strong>components</strong> — reusable pieces of the interface.</p><p><strong>Think of components like LEGO bricks:</strong></p><ul><li>Each component does one thing well</li><li>Components can contain other components</li><li>Changes to one component don't break others</li></ul><p><strong>Main components:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>OutlinePro</strong> — The main \"orchestrator\" that manages everything</li><li><strong>OutlinePane</strong> — The tree view on the left</li><li><strong>ContentPane</strong> — The editor on the right</li><li><strong>SidebarPane</strong> — The outline list on the far left</li><li><strong>NodeItem</strong> — A single node in the tree (used many times)</li></ul><p><strong>Dialog components:</strong></p><p>Each popup window (like Settings, AI dialogs, Research & Import) is its own component that appears when needed and disappears when closed.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "under-the-hood",
      "childrenIds": [
        "tech-components-toolbar"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "10.2"
    },
    "tech-data-flow": {
      "id": "tech-data-flow",
      "name": "How Data Flows",
      "content": "<p>Understanding how information moves through the app:</p><p><strong>1. User makes a change</strong></p><p>You type something, click a button, or drag a node.</p><p><strong>2. Event handler catches it</strong></p><p>React calls a function (like <code>handleUpdateNode</code>) that knows what to do.</p><p><strong>3. State is updated</strong></p><p>The app's \"state\" (all the data it's keeping track of) is updated. In React, this triggers a re-render — the screen redraws to show the new state.</p><p><strong>4. Outline is marked dirty</strong></p><p>The app notes that this outline has unsaved changes.</p><p><strong>5. Auto-save kicks in</strong></p><p>After a 2-second pause, the dirty outlines are written to disk.</p><p><strong>Key principle: Immutability</strong></p><p>When the app updates data, it doesn't change the existing data — it creates a new copy with the changes. This might seem wasteful, but it makes the app more reliable and enables features like undo.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "under-the-hood",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": "10.3"
    },
    "ai-consent-system": {
      "id": "ai-consent-system",
      "name": "AI Data Consent System",
      "content": "<p>Before any AI feature can be used, the app asks for your consent to send data to third-party AI services (Google Gemini, OpenAI, AssemblyAI). This is required by Apple's App Store guidelines.</p><p></p><p><strong>How it works:</strong></p><ul><li><p>On first use of any AI feature, a consent dialog appears explaining which services process your data</p></li><li><p>If you agree, all AI features work normally</p></li><li><p>If you decline, a warning screen lists all features that will be disabled, and asks you to confirm</p></li><li><p>You can change your choice anytime in Settings → Data &amp; Privacy</p></li><li><p>Consent status is stored in localStorage</p></li></ul>",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isExpanded": false,
      "prefix": "7.6"
    },
    "external-mod-detection": {
      "id": "external-mod-detection",
      "name": "External Modification Detection",
      "content": "<p>The app detects when outline files are modified externally (e.g., by Claude Code or another process) while the app is running.</p><p></p><p><strong>How it works:</strong></p><ul><li><p>Every 5 seconds, the app checks the file modification time (mtime) of the current outline on disk</p></li><li><p>If the file has changed since last load, the app automatically reloads it and clears the dirty flag</p></li><li><p>This prevents the app from overwriting external changes with its stale in-memory version</p></li><li><p>The check also runs when the window regains focus</p></li></ul>",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isExpanded": false,
      "prefix": "10.4"
    },
    "search-filters": {
      "id": "search-filters",
      "name": "Search Filters",
      "content": "<p>The search bar (Ctrl/Cmd+F) includes filter toggles that let you narrow what gets searched:</p><p></p><ul><li><p><strong>Names filter</strong> (T icon) — search node titles/names</p></li><li><p><strong>Content filter</strong> (paragraph icon) — search node body content</p></li><li><p>Both are on by default; toggle either off to focus your search</p></li><li><p>At least one must remain on at all times</p></li><li><p>Works with both current-outline and all-outlines search scope</p></li></ul><p><strong>Search as a compress-only view-shaper (2026-06-08, corrected from 2026-06-07):</strong> When you type a search term, the tree unfolds just enough to show the matching nodes plus the chain of ancestors leading down to each one. Every other branch is collapsed so the matches stand out — but every node remains a row in the tree. Nothing is hidden. The user can click any chevron, on any branch, at any time to open it up and explore. Search reshapes the tree by collapsing, never by removing rows from the visible list.</p><p><strong>Why we corrected the design:</strong> the previous (2026-06-07) implementation truly hid non-matching nodes from the tree. That blocked the user from chevron-expanding any branch the filter compressed away — navigation was gated on whether a node happened to match the term. Howard's clarified intent is that search should compress, not block: every branch must remain explorable.</p><p><strong>What restores the full view:</strong></p><ul><li><p>Expand All (Cmd+E on Mac, Ctrl+E on Win/Linux) opens every branch</p></li><li><p>Collapse All (Cmd+Shift+E on Mac, Ctrl+Shift+E on Win/Linux) folds everything</p></li><li><p>Or just chevron-click branches open one at a time</p></li></ul><p><strong>Chained searches still work:</strong> the funnel toggle (\"Search only open nodes\") restricts the next search to currently expanded nodes, letting you chain searches as a logical AND. Searching \"alpha\" then \"beta\" with the funnel on narrows to nodes containing both.</p><p><strong>Implementation:</strong> the shaper only writes <code>isCollapsed</code> on nodes — true for non-matching, non-ancestor nodes that have children; false for matches and their ancestors. There is no longer a hidden-set or status chip; the renderer simply respects each node's <code>isCollapsed</code> flag, which is what makes chevron-expand always work.</p>",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isExpanded": false,
      "prefix": "5.4"
    },
    "second-brain-8232afad": {
      "id": "second-brain-8232afad",
      "name": "Second Brain",
      "content": "<p>The Second Brain is a special outline that acts as a personal knowledge vault. Anything you save from anywhere in the app lands here as a new top-level entry, so you build up a searchable trail of ideas, snippets, and references over time. Three features make it fast and friendly to use: a global quick-capture shortcut, a dashboard that surfaces what's new and what's worth revisiting, and behind-the-scenes auto-tagging that organizes entries without you having to think about it. Each of these reads from or writes to the same Second Brain outline file, which means everything stays in one place and your saves are never locked away in a separate database.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [
        "sb-quick-capture-186c33",
        "sb-dashboard-798f18",
        "sb-auto-tag-104ed1"
      ],
      "isExpanded": false
    },
    "sb-quick-capture-186c33": {
      "id": "sb-quick-capture-186c33",
      "name": "Quick Capture",
      "content": "<p>Quick Capture is a floating dialog that appears from anywhere in the app when you press Cmd+Shift+I. The shortcut is wired up as a global keyboard listener, so it works whether you're editing an outline, browsing the dashboard, or just looking at the menu. When you type something and confirm, the app opens the Second Brain outline behind the scenes, finds (or creates) a node called the Inbox at the very top, and adds your text as a new child entry under it. The Inbox sits above your other saves on purpose, so you always know where fresh captures land. The dialog closes immediately afterward, letting you get back to whatever you were doing without interrupting your flow.</p><p><strong>How to open it without the keyboard (2026-06-06 change):</strong> the standalone Inbox-icon toolbar button was retired. Quick Capture now lives inside the Brain dropdown — click the brain icon in the toolbar and pick \"Quick Capture\". The keyboard shortcut still works the same way; the cognitive order in the menu is Open Second Brain → Quick Capture → Save Selection → Search Second Brain. The reason for the merge: a free-floating Inbox icon competed with the brain icon two slots away and confused new users about whether \"capture\" and \"second brain\" were the same thing. Folding the action into the brain menu makes the relationship obvious and frees up a toolbar slot.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "second-brain-8232afad",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isExpanded": false
    },
    "sb-dashboard-798f18": {
      "id": "sb-dashboard-798f18",
      "name": "Second Brain Dashboard",
      "content": "<p>The Second Brain Dashboard is a view you open from the Brain menu. When it loads, it reads the Second Brain outline directly and walks through every top-level entry under the root. From that traversal it builds four panels: a total count of entries, a list of recent saves from the last seven days (using each node's creation timestamp), a revisit pile of older entries the app pulls forward so they don't get forgotten, and a top-tags summary built by counting the tag values stored in each node's metadata. Every item in every panel is clickable; clicking jumps the main outline view straight to that entry. Because the dashboard reads the outline live, it always reflects the current state of your Second Brain.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "second-brain-8232afad",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isExpanded": false
    },
    "sb-auto-tag-104ed1": {
      "id": "sb-auto-tag-104ed1",
      "name": "Smart Auto-Tagging",
      "content": "<p>Smart Auto-Tagging runs every time something is saved to the Second Brain, whether through the Cmd+Shift+B save shortcut or a Quick Capture entry. As soon as the new node is written, the app quietly sends the saved text to Gemini and asks for one to three short, hyphenated tags that describe the content. When the response comes back, those tags are written into the new node's metadata silently, with no popup or confirmation, so the save still feels instant. The dashboard then picks those tags up automatically the next time it tallies its top-tags panel. If the AI call fails or Gemini is unreachable, the save still succeeds, the node just goes in untagged and life carries on.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "second-brain-8232afad",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isExpanded": false
    },
    "ai-livebooks": {
      "id": "ai-livebooks",
      "name": "LIVE BOOKS (Refresh from Web)",
      "content": "LIVE BOOKS is the app's first \"transform engine\" feature. The idea: a static document goes stale, so the user picks a node, and the app rewrites that node plus everything under it against the latest information from the web, but only after the user approves a preview.\n\nHow it is built: there is a generalized, reusable engine (src/lib/transforms/transform-engine.ts) that knows how to walk a node and its descendants, decide which nodes are eligible, run a 'transformer' on each one, and apply approved changes back. The engine does not know what 'refresh' means - it just runs whatever transformer it is given. The actual refresh logic lives in a small transformer (src/lib/transforms/refresh-transform.ts) that calls a server action. This separation is deliberate: a future Translation feature will be a second transformer plugged into the exact same engine, with no engine changes.\n\nThe flow: the user opens the LIVE BOOKS dialog (toolbar Import menu, command palette, or Cmd/Ctrl+Shift+R; moved out of the Smart Tools/AI menu on 2026-06-06 because it brings web content INTO existing nodes). They pick Merge (revise in place, keep what's still good) or Overwrite (rewrite from scratch). The engine asks the AI - cloud Gemini with live Google Search grounding by default, local Ollama as a fallback - to propose new content for each node. Nothing is touched yet. The dialog shows a before/after for every node; the user accepts or rejects each one, then applies. Only then does the node map change.\n\nSafety: when a person edits a node by hand, the app quietly marks that node as 'user-edited'. LIVE BOOKS skips those nodes so it never overwrites the user's own words, unless they explicitly opt a node back in. Every refreshed node also records which model produced it and the real source URLs used; that information is stored on the node itself, so it is saved and exported along with everything else, and a small Sources chip on the node reveals it. Local refreshes have no internet, so they honestly report 'no web sources' instead of inventing citations. LIVE BOOKS is personal and local - it only ever changes the user's own copy.",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "ai-features",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "tier-enforcement": {
      "id": "tier-enforcement",
      "name": "Plans, Tiers & Enforcement",
      "content": "<p>IdiamPro's launch model uses a single, simple unit: <strong>1 generation = 1 user-initiated AI action</strong> (one Help-chat round-trip, one LIVE BOOKS refresh of any number of nodes, one Translate of any branch, one Tell-AI command). The fan-out of model calls underneath doesn't count — it's the button press that matters.</p><p></p><p><strong>The four user-visible tiers:</strong></p><ul><li><p><strong>Free trial</strong> — 25 generations TOTAL (one-time, not monthly). When you run out, you must add a free API key (Gemini takes about a minute) or upgrade.</p></li><li><p><strong>Free + your own key (BYOK)</strong> — Unlimited. Adding any provider key in Settings → AI Service Keys instantly bypasses the counter. You pay the provider directly; we charge nothing.</p></li><li><p><strong>Student ($4.99/mo)</strong> — 200 generations per month. .edu email + honor checkbox at signup (real verification post-launch).</p></li><li><p><strong>Pro ($9.99/mo)</strong> — 1,000 generations per month, Pro-only features (podcast generation, image generation), and priority support. Pro+BYOK bypasses the counter entirely.</p></li></ul><p></p><p><strong>The pieces under the hood:</strong></p><ul><li><p><em>tier-detection.ts</em> — figures out which tier a user is on (checks for a paid tier ID, then for any BYOK key, falls back to free-trial). Defines the caps (25 / unlimited / 200 / 1000).</p></li><li><p><em>ai-usage-counter.ts</em> — the calendar-month bucket in localStorage. Resets at the 1st of each month, midnight in the user's LOCAL timezone. Stores <code>{ monthKey, count }</code> under <code>idiampro-ai-usage-counter-v1</code>. Safe-defaults: any storage glitch returns a fresh zero record (never blocks the user).</p></li><li><p><em>use-ai-usage-gate.tsx</em> — the single hook every AI call site uses. One call: <code>if (!gate({ feature: 'helpChat' })) return;</code> runs the Pro-only check, the BYOK / local exemption, the hard-block check, increments the counter, and fires the 80% soft-warn toast — all in one place. Headless variant available for non-React contexts.</p></li><li><p><em>Settings → AI Usage</em> — the user-facing display: tier name, X of Y used, reset date, progress bar (emerald → amber at 80% → red at cap). BYOK users see \"Unlimited — using your own API key.\"</p></li></ul><p></p><p><strong>Gate-hit experience (locked product decisions):</strong></p><ul><li><p>Soft-warn toast the first time the user crosses 80% of their cap (8000ms duration).</p></li><li><p>Hard-block upgrade dialog at 100%. Conversational copy that points to BYOK as the immediate escape hatch — no CLI-speak.</p></li><li><p>Pro-only features (podcast, image gen) on lower tiers: <strong>visible with a Pro badge</strong>; clicking opens the upgrade dialog. We don't hide them — better for discovery + upsell.</p></li><li><p>Fail-open: if the gate itself throws or RevenueCat is unreachable, allow the action. Better to occasionally over-serve than to lock paying users out.</p></li></ul><p></p><p><strong>Always exempt — never counted, never blocked:</strong> any BYOK key on any tier, or the user picking the local Ollama provider.</p><p></p><p><strong>Where the AI call sites are gated:</strong> Help chat, Knowledge chat, LIVE BOOKS refresh, Translate, Tell-AI command bar, Research & Import, Generate Outline, Expand Content, Create Content for Descendants, Podcast Generation (Pro-only), Image Generation (Pro-only). Each call site invokes <code>gate({ feature: '...' })</code> as the first thing in its handler.</p><p></p><p><strong>Today's state:</strong> the counter is LIVE — Free-trial users really do see X of 25 and hit the hard-block at 25. BYOK works fully. The Student and Pro tier IDs need a Clerk webhook (still pending) to be set, so today every user is treated as Free-trial unless they add a BYOK key. The \"Upgrade\" button is a polite \"checkout coming soon\" placeholder.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "under-the-hood",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "launch-metrics": {
      "id": "launch-metrics",
      "name": "Launch Metrics Dashboard (admin)",
      "content": "The <strong>Launch Metrics</strong> page is an internal-only dashboard for the people running IdiamPro. It lives at the URL path <code>/admin/metrics</code> and shows the seven numbers that matter most during launch week, all on one screen, big and readable.\n<p></p>\n<p><strong>What it shows:</strong> Signups this week, activation rate (share of new signups who created an outline on day one), day-1 retention, day-7 retention, free-to-paid conversion, AI runs in the last 24 hours, and monthly recurring revenue. Each one is a card with the big number, a tiny trend arrow showing change vs. the previous comparable period, and a one-sentence description of what it means.</p>\n<p><strong>Who can see it:</strong> Only admins. The page checks a small flag in browser storage (<code>isAdmin</code>). Anyone else gets a polite \"access required\" card explaining what to do. This is a v1 gate — proper role-based access will replace it when real auth (Clerk) is wired in.</p>\n<p><strong>Refresh:</strong> A Refresh button at the top right pulls a new snapshot. A \"Last updated N min ago\" line right next to it tells you how stale the data is. Nothing auto-polls — you decide when to look.</p>\n<p><strong>Data today vs. data later:</strong> Every number on the page is currently a placeholder labelled \"Demo\" — there's also a yellow banner at the top of the page that says so. Real telemetry needs Clerk (for signups and retention), RevenueCat (for subscriptions and MRR), and an internal events backend (for activation and AI volume), and none of those are wired yet. The page reads its numbers from a small helper module (<code>src/lib/launch-metrics.ts</code>) where each metric is a separate function. When real data sources come online, those functions get rewritten one at a time and the page itself doesn't change.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "48b45703-8432-4467-a3e8-96caca3d777b": {
      "id": "48b45703-8432-4467-a3e8-96caca3d777b",
      "name": "Cross-outline link nodes + sidebar nesting + value-based naming (2026-06-04)",
      "content": "What it is, in everyday language:\n\nOutlines used to be islands — each one a separate document with no way to reference another. As of 2026-06-04, an outline can hold a special \"link node\" that points at another outline in your library. Clicking the link jumps you straight to the target outline, the same way clicking a link on a web page takes you to a new page.\n\nHow a user makes one:\n- Open the toolbar's Import menu (the down-arrow book icon) and choose \"Link to Outline…\", or right-click any node in the tree and pick \"Insert Link to Outline…\".\n- A picker dialog lists your other outlines (the one you're already in is hidden so you can't accidentally link to yourself).\n- Pick an outline. A new node appears under whatever you had selected, named after the outline you picked. Rename it freely.\n\nWhat it shows on screen:\n- The link node uses a distinctive arrow-out-of-box icon so it's easy to tell apart from regular nodes.\n- The node's name is the clickable label.\n\nWhat happens on click:\n- The app navigates to the linked outline and selects its root node — exactly the same as if you had clicked the outline name in the sidebar.\n- If the linked outline has been deleted at some point, clicking shows a polite \"The outline you linked to has been deleted\" message and stays put. Nothing crashes.\n\nPHASE 2 — Sidebar nesting of linked outlines (same date):\n\nOnce an outline contains one or more link nodes, the targets of those links also appear INDENTED beneath the parent outline in the left sidebar. The sidebar list still shows every outline at the top level (so a linked outline doesn't disappear from the main list just because something points at it), but it ALSO appears as a nested child under each parent that links to it.\n\nHow it looks:\n- A small chevron (▸/▾) appears on the left of any sidebar row that has linked children. Click it to expand or collapse the nested branch. The open/closed state is remembered across sessions, per outline, in browser local storage.\n- Nested rows are indented by a fixed amount per depth level (~16 pixels) and show the same arrow-out-of-box icon used by link nodes, so the visual story matches.\n- Clicking the NAME of a nested row loads that outline (same as clicking it at the top level). Clicking the CHEVRON only toggles expansion — it doesn't switch outlines.\n\nMulti-parent and dedupe:\n- If two different outlines both link to the same target, the target appears nested under BOTH parents. We chose correctness over visual minimalism — if a user puts a link in two places, they expect to see it in two places.\n- If a single parent has two link nodes both pointing to the same target, the sidebar shows that target once under that parent (the duplicate is hidden — a user almost never wants to see the same nested branch twice in a row).\n\nCircular references:\n- If outline A links to B and B links back to A (or any longer cycle: A → B → C → A), the nested view stops at the second occurrence and shows it as a muted, non-clickable leaf with a small circular-arrow indicator and a tooltip explaining it's already shown above. This means no infinite-render loop and a clear visual cue that there's a loop in the structure.\n\nSearch:\n- The sidebar search box matches outline names regardless of whether they're top-level or nested. A nested branch is expanded automatically when its name (or any of its descendants' names) matches the query.\n\nNot yet:\n- Inline content preview of the linked outline (its actual nodes, shown in the tree under the link) is still a future phase.\n- The user's AI features (\"Ask Your Outlines\", \"Quick Command\") do NOT traverse cross-outline links yet — that's also a future enhancement.\n\nNAMING PASS (same date) — values-over-mechanism labels:\n- The sparkles toolbar menu is now called \"Smart Tools\" instead of \"AI Features\". The sparkles icon is unchanged.\n- The natural-language command bar item inside that menu is now \"Quick Command\" instead of \"Tell AI…\". The keyboard shortcut (Cmd+K) is unchanged.\n- The cross-outline question feature is now \"Ask Your Outlines\" instead of \"Knowledge Chat\".\n- The web-refresh feature shows as \"Refresh from Web\" in every user-facing surface (the menu item, the dialog title, the command palette entry). Internal code identifiers still use the old \"LIVE BOOKS\" name — that's a developer-side convention only.\n- The \"Ask AI (Cmd+K)\" toolbar tooltip was kept as-is because that wording remains the most discoverable for first-time users.\n\nThe point: labels describe what a button DOES for the user, not how it works under the hood.",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "onboarding-emails-2026-06-05": {
      "id": "onboarding-emails-2026-06-05",
      "name": "Onboarding emails (welcome + 3-email drip series, 2026-06-05)",
      "content": "What it is, in everyday language:\n\nWhen someone signs up for IdiamPro, the app sends them a short series of emails to help them get started — a welcome message right away, and three follow-up tips spread over the first two weeks. After that, no more onboarding emails ever. That's the whole feature.\n\nThe four emails:\n\n1. Welcome email — fires the moment a new account is created. Greets the person by first name (or 'Hi there' if no name was captured), thanks them for joining, and gives three quick-start actions: create your first outline, try Smart Tools, watch a two-minute intro video. One big blue 'Open IdiamPro' button.\n\n2. Day 3 — 'Stop maintaining documents by hand'. One feature highlight on Refresh from Web. The idea is to surface one useful capability the user might've missed in the first few days. Just enough copy to explain what it does and one button to try it.\n\n3. Day 7 — 'Three power-user tips'. Quick Capture (Cmd+Shift+I), Research & Import (combine many sources into one outline), and Ask Your Outlines. Each tip is a short paragraph with the keyboard shortcut and the menu path.\n\n4. Day 14 — 'Two weeks in — a quick note on Pro'. A soft, conversational explanation of what's behind the Pro tier ($9.99/mo) — podcast generation, image generation, 1,000 AI generations a month, priority support. Mentions the BYOK escape hatch up front so nobody feels cornered into a paid plan.\n\nHow the send happens:\n\nWhen someone signs up, Clerk (the sign-in service) calls a small endpoint at /api/webhooks/clerk. That endpoint verifies the request came from Clerk (using a shared signing secret), reads the new user's email + first name, and asks the email layer to send the welcome message. The email layer in turn calls Resend (a transactional email service) over the HTTPS API and Resend takes care of actually delivering the message.\n\nThe three drip emails work the same way, except they're scheduled by Vercel Cron — Vercel's built-in 'run this URL on a schedule' feature. Once a day, Vercel calls /api/cron/drip; that endpoint walks the user list, figures out who's at day 3, day 7, or day 14 of their account, and sends each of them the matching email. Welcome is the only one that's strictly required on launch day; the drip schedule will be wired up post-launch.\n\nUnsubscribe — how it works:\n\nEvery email has a one-click 'Unsubscribe' link in the footer (legally required in the US under CAN-SPAM; also just the right thing to do). The link points at /unsubscribe and carries two pieces of information in the URL: the user's id, and a short cryptographic signature of that id. When the page loads, it checks the signature is real (so nobody can guess unsubscribe URLs for other users), records that the person has opted out, and shows a friendly 'You're unsubscribed' message. From that moment on, the send layer skips that user entirely — no more onboarding emails will go to that address, ever.\n\nUnsubscribing only affects the onboarding series. The app itself keeps working exactly the same.\n\nEnv-gated — costs nothing when off:\n\nThe whole layer is gated on environment variables. With RESEND_API_KEY not set, every send is a no-op log line that says 'Resend not configured — skipping' and returns successfully. Signup still works, the webhook still receives events, the cron still runs — there's just no email actually going out. This means the app behaves exactly as it does today until Howard sets the keys. Same philosophy as Sentry, Clerk, and Stripe.\n\nWhere the unsubscribe list lives:\n\nFor launch, the unsubscribe list is a small JSON file under .idiampro/unsubscribed.json (next to the running process). This is fine for the volumes we'll see in the first few months. Post-launch, when there's a real user database, it moves into a single table column without changing any of the calling code — every consumer talks to four little functions (isUnsubscribed, markUnsubscribed, markResubscribed, _resetUnsubscribeStoreForTest), and only those functions need to change to repoint at the database.\n\nNot yet:\n\n- Sending emails to users who signed up before the email layer existed (no batch backfill).\n- Localised email copy. All four emails are English-only for now.\n- HTML preview tool inside the app for admins.\n- A 'pause emails for N days' option (only unsubscribe-all is available today).",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "web-payment-stripe-revenuecat-2026-06-05": {
      "id": "web-payment-stripe-revenuecat-2026-06-05",
      "name": "Web payment — Stripe + RevenueCat (2026-06-05)",
      "content": "What it is, in everyday language:\n\nIdiamPro now has a real upgrade page on the web. Anyone using the app in a web browser, or in the Mac/Windows/Linux desktop version, can pick a plan and pay with a credit card (or Apple Pay or Google Pay) without leaving the app. On iPhone and iPad, the same upgrade buttons open Apple's purchase sheet instead of a web checkout — Apple's rules require iOS apps to use Apple's own in-app purchase system, so we honor that.\n\nThe key idea: regardless of WHERE someone pays (web, Mac, iPhone), one service called RevenueCat keeps track of WHICH plan they're on. That way, if you pay on your laptop and then open IdiamPro on your iPhone, your iPhone already knows you're a paid user. No re-buying, no syncing headaches.\n\nThe two payment systems:\n\n1. STRIPE — handles web and desktop payments. When the user clicks 'Upgrade to Pro' on the web /upgrade page, the app creates a Stripe Checkout session (a secure hosted payment page) and sends the user there. Stripe handles the card details, the security, the receipts — we never see the user's card number. After payment, Stripe sends a webhook (a server-to-server notification) back to IdiamPro saying 'this user just bought Pro'.\n\n2. APPLE IN-APP PURCHASE — handles iPhone and iPad payments. The same upgrade page detects when it's running on iOS and opens Apple's purchase sheet instead. Apple takes its 30% (15% after the first year) and handles the receipt. RevenueCat's iOS plugin tells the rest of the app the user is now paid.\n\nWhy two systems? Apple's App Store rules (guideline 3.1.1) require iOS apps to use Apple's in-app purchase for digital subscriptions — we can't use Stripe on iOS even if we wanted to (the app would get rejected). On web, Stripe is the modern standard and takes a much smaller cut (~3%). So we use the best fit for each platform and RevenueCat ties them together.\n\nThe three plans on the upgrade page:\n\n- Free (BYOK) — $0 forever. You bring your own AI key (Gemini, OpenAI, etc.) and get unlimited generations because you're paying the AI provider directly.\n- Student — $4.99/month. 200 AI generations per month, AI key included, .edu email required.\n- Pro — $9.99/month, or $89/year (save 25%). 1,000 AI generations per month, podcast generation, image generation, priority support.\n\nManage Subscription:\n\nInside the app, Settings → Account now has a 'Manage Subscription' button for paid users. On web/desktop it opens Stripe's hosted Customer Portal — that's the same kind of page you'd see if you were managing a Netflix or Substack subscription. From there you can cancel, change plan (e.g. monthly to annual), update your card, or download past invoices. On iOS the same button routes to Apple's Subscriptions screen (the one buried in Settings → Apple ID → Subscriptions).\n\nWhat happens when the user actually pays:\n\n1. User clicks 'Upgrade to Pro' on /upgrade. The app POSTs to a small server route (/api/billing/checkout) which creates a Stripe Checkout session and returns the secure URL.\n2. The browser redirects to Stripe's hosted payment page. The user enters card details, or uses Apple Pay / Google Pay (Stripe surfaces those automatically — no extra wiring on our side).\n3. Stripe charges the card, then redirects the user to /upgrade/success in IdiamPro.\n4. In the background, Stripe also sends a webhook to /api/billing/webhook. That route verifies the message is really from Stripe (using a shared signing secret), figures out which plan was purchased, and calls RevenueCat's API to grant the user the matching entitlement ('pro' or 'student').\n5. The /upgrade/success page calls a small function called refreshTier(), which re-reads the user's current entitlement so the new tier is live immediately in the app — no need to refresh the page or sign out and back in.\n\nThe 'stub mode' safety net:\n\nThe whole billing layer is gated on environment variables (the same approach used for Sentry, Clerk, and the email layer). With STRIPE_SECRET_KEY or REVENUECAT_API_KEY unset, every billing endpoint logs a clear 'not configured — stubbing response' message and returns a mock success URL. The /upgrade/success page detects stub mode and seeds the user's tier in browser storage so the rest of the app behaves as if the user just paid. This lets the entire upgrade UX be exercised end-to-end in development and tests before Howard sets up the real Stripe and RevenueCat accounts. When the real keys land, stub mode silently turns off and real payments take over.\n\nThe little details that matter:\n\n- Webhook idempotency: Stripe sometimes retries the same notification (network blips). The webhook handler remembers the last 500 event IDs in memory and ignores duplicates, so a single payment never provisions the entitlement twice.\n- Cancel-anytime: The Customer Portal lets the user cancel at any moment, with no questions asked. When they cancel, they keep access until the end of the billing period; then a 'subscription deleted' webhook fires and RevenueCat revokes the entitlement automatically.\n- Payment failed: If a renewal charge fails, Stripe emails the user and we get an 'invoice.payment_failed' webhook. For v1 this is logged for follow-up; a 'your payment failed, update card' banner in the app is a post-launch polish item.\n- The /upgrade/cancel page: If the user backs out of Stripe Checkout without paying, they land on a friendly 'no charge made' page with a soft re-pitch of the Pro features (no guilt-trip, no pressure).\n\nNot yet:\n\n- The real Stripe account doesn't exist yet — Howard needs to create one, set up the three products (Pro Monthly, Pro Annual, Student Monthly), copy the Price IDs into the env vars. Same for RevenueCat. Until then, everything runs in stub mode and no real money moves.\n- The user's app account isn't linked to their Stripe customer yet. Once Clerk auth is fully wired, every Checkout will carry a client_reference_id pointing at the signed-in user, so the webhook can map payments back to accounts automatically.\n- A 'past-due' banner inside the app for users whose card declined on renewal.\n- iOS native purchase wiring — today the iOS path is a toast that says 'opening the in-app purchase flow'; the actual call to RevenueCat's Capacitor plugin lands when the iOS build is set up post-launch.",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "auth-wall-section-b7c0ebd8": {
      "id": "auth-wall-section-b7c0ebd8",
      "name": "Authentication",
      "content": "<p><strong>The outliner is gated behind a sign-in.</strong> The marketing pages (homepage, /marketing, /pricing, /privacy, /upgrade, /stress-test) stay public so anyone can read about IdiamPro and decide to sign up; but to actually open the /app outliner or any /admin tool you need an account.</p><p><strong>Public vs private routes.</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Public</strong>: /, /marketing, /pricing, /privacy, /upgrade and its success/cancel pages, /stress-test, /unsubscribe, /signin, /signup, plus the webhook endpoints (/api/webhooks/* and /api/billing/webhook) which are machine-to-machine calls from Clerk and Stripe.</li><li><strong>Private (sign-in required)</strong>: /app/*, /admin/*, and the AI endpoints that operate on user content - /api/help-chat, /api/knowledge-chat, /api/synthesize-podcast, /api/generate-podcast, /api/extract-pdf, /api/billing/checkout, /api/billing/portal.</li></ul><p><strong>Sign-up to tier flow.</strong> The homepage hero shows a primary <em>Sign up to try IdiamPro free</em> button (or <em>Open IdiamPro</em> if the visitor is already signed in). New accounts land directly in /app on the Free trial tier (25 generations, one-time). They can add a BYOK key to bypass the counter, or upgrade to Student ($4.99/mo) or Pro ($9.99/mo) from /upgrade.</p><p><strong>How the wall actually works.</strong> A Next.js middleware (src/middleware.ts) matches every request, decides whether the path is protected, and either lets it through, redirects an unauthenticated browser to /signin (preserving the original URL in a redirect_url query param), or returns a 401 JSON response for API routes. Auth state comes from Clerk via @clerk/nextjs/server's auth() helper.</p><p><strong>Stub-safe pattern.</strong> Auth is gated on env vars in the same style as the Sentry integration. With CLERK_SECRET_KEY and NEXT_PUBLIC_CLERK_PUBLISHABLE_KEY unset, the middleware logs a single dev warning and lets everyone through; the Account avatar in the toolbar doesn't render; and the sign-in / sign-up pages show a friendly 'being set up' notice. The moment both env vars are set in Vercel, the wall goes live in production with no code change.</p><p><strong>Sign-out.</strong> A Clerk UserButton lives in the top-right of the app toolbar (at the right edge, immediately after the More-tools overflow). Signing out lands the user back on the homepage [/].</p><p><strong>Invite-only access (beta gating).</strong> On top of the sign-in wall, IdiamPro is in invite-only beta: only emails Howard has explicitly approved may complete signup. There are two enforcement layers. (1) The /signup page asks for an email first and POSTs it to /api/invite-check; if the email is not on the allowlist the page shows a conversational gate message ('IdiamPro is in invite-only beta right now. Your email isn't on the invite list yet — drop us a note at hello@2ndbrainware.com and we'll get you in.') and never hands off to Clerk. (2) The Clerk user.created webhook re-runs the same allowlist check as defense in depth: if anyone navigates around the page UI and creates an account anyway, the webhook calls Clerk's REST API to delete the account immediately, BEFORE sending the welcome email. Storage v1: the comma-separated INVITE_ALLOWLIST env var (exact, case-insensitive matching — no wildcards, no domain-level matching). Editing the value in Vercel and redeploying is how Howard approves a new tester. Extension point v1.1: a self-service /admin/invites dashboard backed by a database — the data layer (isEmailAllowed / getAllowedEmails in src/lib/access/allowlist.ts) already abstracts storage so callers don't change. Stub-safe: with INVITE_ALLOWLIST unset OR empty the check returns 'allowed' for everyone, matching the rest of IdiamPro's env-gated layers (Sentry / Clerk / Stripe / Resend) and giving zero runtime overhead until Howard flips the gate on.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "discovery-hints-2026-06-05": {
      "id": "discovery-hints-2026-06-05",
      "name": "Discovery Hints (\"Did You Know?\" tips)",
      "content": "<p><strong>How SecondBrainWare teaches you the app without a tutorial.</strong></p><p>The app surfaces small <em>discovery cards</em> in the lower-right corner the first time you reach a feature worth knowing about. Each card has a violet sparkle, the eyebrow <strong>\"Did You Know?\"</strong>, a short title, a one-sentence explanation, a <strong>\"Don't show me this again\" checkbox</strong>, and a <strong>Got it</strong> button. There is no auto-dismiss — the card waits patiently until you decide.</p><p><strong>v1 ships five tips:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>First text selection in the editor</strong> → \"Reformat with AI is here\" (points at the violet wand at the left end of the bubble menu)</li><li><strong>Six seconds later</strong> → \"Smart Tools = your AI toolkit\" (points at the sparkle icon in the toolbar)</li><li><strong>First outline created</strong> → \"Link one outline to another\" (the cross-outline link node)</li><li><strong>Ten seconds later</strong> → \"Import and Export live in the toolbar\" (where Research &amp; Import, Backup All, Share Branch, etc. live)</li><li><strong>First time you open a BYOK key entry</strong> → \"Bring your own API key for unlimited use\"</li></ul><p><strong>Two-tier dismissal (2026-06-05 refinement).</strong> Realistically a single \"Got it\" isn't enough — sometimes a tip needs to surface a few times before it really sticks, sometimes the user is sure they're done with it forever. So the card now offers two paths:</p><ul><li><strong>Click Got it with the checkbox UNCHECKED → soft dismiss.</strong> The card closes; the same tip is eligible to fire again the next time its trigger occurs.</li><li><strong>Tick the box, then click Got it → hard dismiss.</strong> The tip id is added to a persistent <em>hard-dismissed</em> list in browser storage and the tip never appears again, even after a Professional-mode toggle.</li></ul><p>There is intentionally no persisted \"soft-dismissed\" set — soft simply means \"not in the active queue right now,\" and the next trigger fires re-enqueues. This keeps the state machine tiny.</p><p><strong>Professional mode (the master switch).</strong> Settings → Tips → Professional mode is the override. Turning it ON clears everything currently visible and stops all future hints. Turning it OFF resumes normal behaviour: hints fire on triggers again — but the hard-dismissed list is untouched, so anything the user explicitly marked \"Don't show again\" stays hidden. A brief confirmation card (\"Welcome tips re-enabled — You'll see them on next-trigger — except the ones you marked 'Don't show again.'\") makes the change non-silent.</p><p><strong>Architecturally,</strong> the registry lives in <em>src/lib/discovery/hints.ts</em>; the React provider + global <em>fireDiscovery()</em> event bus is in <em>src/hooks/use-discovery.tsx</em> (storage keys <em>discovery:hardDismissedHints</em> and <em>discovery:professionalMode</em>; legacy <em>discovery:dismissedHints</em> is migrated to hardDismissed on first read). The sticky toast renderer is a separate component (<em>src/components/discovery-toast.tsx</em>) mounted once at app shell level — the existing transient toast system is unchanged.</p>",
      "type": "node",
      "parentId": "ai-features",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "tech-components-toolbar": {
      "id": "tech-components-toolbar",
      "name": "Toolbar — Responsive Tiered Layout",
      "content": "<p><strong>The Toolbar — Responsive across screen sizes (added 2026-06-06)</strong></p><p>The toolbar at the top of the outline pane is built from icon buttons grouped in two short rows. The clever part is that it <em>adapts to screen width</em> using a three-tier visibility system, so phones, tablets, and desktops each get a sensible set of buttons rather than a one-size-fits-all toolbar that runs off the edge of small screens.</p><p><strong>How the tiers work:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>Anchors (always visible):</strong> the sidebar toggle on the far left and the account avatar on the far right. These are fixed reference points so users always know where the toolbar starts and ends.</li><li><strong>Tier 1 (always visible):</strong> the most frequently-used actions — Ask AI (chat bubble), Plus (add node), Delete, Search.</li><li><strong>Tier 2 (tablet and up, hides on phone):</strong> Import, Export, Focus Mode, Show or hide all, Share branch, Command palette, Second Brain, Smart Tools.</li><li><strong>Tier 3 (desktop only, hides on phone and tablet):</strong> Settings, Help. (The Wrench / Refresh User Guide menu was retired 2026-06-07 — the User Guide is now read-only and reloads from the bundled app version on every launch, so a manual refresh is no longer needed.)</li></ul><p><strong>The overflow menu:</strong> when any tier is hidden, a \"More tools\" button (three horizontal dots, just to the left of the avatar) appears. Clicking it opens a popup containing every hidden item, so nothing is ever truly out of reach. On desktop the overflow disappears because everything already fits inline.</p><p><strong>The breakpoints</strong> come from Tailwind CSS: <code>sm</code> = 640 pixels (phone → tablet) and <code>lg</code> = 1024 pixels (tablet → desktop). Each button carries a CSS class like <code>hidden sm:inline-flex</code> or <code>hidden lg:inline-flex</code> that tells the browser exactly when to show it. Resizing the window is instantaneous — no JavaScript runs, the browser just re-applies the rules.</p><p><strong>Keyboard shortcuts are independent of visibility:</strong> Cmd+K, Cmd+F, Cmd+E, Cmd+Shift+E, Cmd+Shift+F, Cmd+Shift+I, etc. fire regardless of whether the matching button is inline or buried in the overflow menu. The handler always runs.</p>",
      "type": "item",
      "parentId": "tech-components",
      "childrenIds": []
    },
    "tech-stack-platform-strategy-2026-06-06": {
      "id": "tech-stack-platform-strategy-2026-06-06",
      "name": "Technology Stack & Platform Strategy",
      "content": "<p><strong>The canonical plain-language explanation of how IdiamPro is built and why this stack lets one team ship to every platform at once.</strong></p><p><em>Added 2026-06-06. Mirrored briefly in BizDev, Killer Features, Planning, and Bootstrap Plan — this is the source of truth.</em></p>",
      "type": "standard",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [
        "tech-stack-glance-2026-06-06",
        "tech-stack-desktop-2026-06-06",
        "tech-stack-ios-2026-06-06",
        "tech-stack-web-2026-06-06",
        "tech-stack-backend-2026-06-06",
        "tech-stack-why-2026-06-06",
        "node-q4sbxzff-mq2y5mz2"
      ],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": null
    },
    "tech-stack-glance-2026-06-06": {
      "id": "tech-stack-glance-2026-06-06",
      "name": "Tech stack at a glance",
      "content": "<p><strong>There is no Python anywhere in IdiamPro.</strong> Zero.</p><p>The core app is <strong>TypeScript with React and Next.js</strong> — JavaScript family, not Python. Everything you see, everything that responds to your taps and clicks, every outline you open, every AI feature you trigger — all of it runs on the same TypeScript codebase, regardless of which device you happen to be holding.</p><p>The platform-specific shells (Electron for desktop, Capacitor for iOS, Vercel for web) are thin wrappers around that one codebase. The strategic upshot: <strong>write once, deploy everywhere</strong>.</p>",
      "type": "standard",
      "parentId": "tech-stack-platform-strategy-2026-06-06",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": null
    },
    "tech-stack-desktop-2026-06-06": {
      "id": "tech-stack-desktop-2026-06-06",
      "name": "macOS, Windows, and Linux desktop (Electron)",
      "content": "<p>The desktop versions are wrapped in <strong>Electron</strong> — Chromium browser engine plus a Node.js runtime, glued together into a single app window.</p><ul><li>Electron has a \"main process\" (the part that manages windows, menus, files) and a \"renderer process\" (the part that draws the UI). <strong>Both run JavaScript/TypeScript</strong> — no native code switching.</li><li>The same React UI that runs in the browser runs inside Electron's window. The same outliner, the same editor, the same AI features.</li><li>One TypeScript codebase produces a Mac DMG, a Windows installer, and a Linux AppImage with build-config differences only.</li></ul>",
      "type": "standard",
      "parentId": "tech-stack-platform-strategy-2026-06-06",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": null
    },
    "tech-stack-ios-2026-06-06": {
      "id": "tech-stack-ios-2026-06-06",
      "name": "iOS (Capacitor)",
      "content": "<p>iOS is wrapped in <strong>Capacitor</strong> — a thin native shell that hosts the existing web app inside a <strong>WKWebView</strong> (the same web engine Safari uses).</p><ul><li>Capacitor generates a small amount of Swift boilerplate for the AppDelegate and a few plugins, but it's stub code — there's essentially no iOS app logic to maintain.</li><li>The actual outliner, editor, AI features — all the same TypeScript/React running inside the iOS webview.</li><li>When a new feature ships on the web, it ships on iOS at the same time. No separate iOS team, no parallel codebase, no version lag.</li></ul><p>Android is compatible by design via Capacitor but the Android project is not yet scaffolded — when it is, it will be the same pattern.</p>",
      "type": "standard",
      "parentId": "tech-stack-platform-strategy-2026-06-06",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": null
    },
    "tech-stack-web-2026-06-06": {
      "id": "tech-stack-web-2026-06-06",
      "name": "Web (Next.js + Vercel)",
      "content": "<p>The web version is the same Next.js app, served by <strong>Vercel</strong>. Every <code>git push</code> to main triggers an automatic deploy. No build server to babysit, no manual deploy steps.</p><p>Because Electron and Capacitor both wrap this same Next.js app, the web build is effectively the \"reference implementation\" — fixing a bug on the web fixes it everywhere.</p>",
      "type": "standard",
      "parentId": "tech-stack-platform-strategy-2026-06-06",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": null
    },
    "tech-stack-backend-2026-06-06": {
      "id": "tech-stack-backend-2026-06-06",
      "name": "Backend functions",
      "content": "<p>The backend — the few server actions and API routes (help-chat, billing webhooks, email sender, etc.) — runs as <strong>Node.js serverless functions on Vercel</strong>.</p><p>Still TypeScript. Still the same codebase. Functions spin up on demand, run for milliseconds, and disappear — no servers to maintain, no scaling configuration.</p><p>Note: nothing in this stack would conflict with Python backend microservices or ML pipelines if added later — Vercel functions can call any backend. But the app itself is JavaScript/TypeScript through and through.</p>",
      "type": "standard",
      "parentId": "tech-stack-platform-strategy-2026-06-06",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": null
    },
    "tech-stack-why-2026-06-06": {
      "id": "tech-stack-why-2026-06-06",
      "name": "Why this stack: write once, deploy everywhere",
      "content": "<p><strong>The strategic significance:</strong> when a feature is shipped, the work happens ONCE in TypeScript and lands on all four platforms simultaneously — web, Mac, Windows, Linux, iOS.</p><ul><li>The team doesn't write iOS code separately and re-write it for macOS and again for web. That's the whole point of the Electron + Capacitor stack.</li><li>One engineer can keep parity across every platform. A four-team org isn't needed.</li><li>Bug fixes propagate to every platform automatically.</li><li>Feature parity is the default state, not an aspirational goal.</li></ul><p>This is the single most important architectural decision in the project. It is what makes a solo developer (or a tiny team) capable of competing with multi-million-dollar outliner companies that staff a separate native team per platform.</p>",
      "type": "standard",
      "parentId": "tech-stack-platform-strategy-2026-06-06",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": null
    },
    "node-q4sbxzff-mq2y5mz2": {
      "id": "node-q4sbxzff-mq2y5mz2",
      "name": "How users get updates on each platform",
      "content": "<p><strong>How users actually receive a new version on each platform — the distribution-mechanics dimension.</strong></p><p>Shipping a feature is not the same as users getting it. The update path is a different problem on every platform, and the friction varies by an order of magnitude. Here is what actually happens after a <code>git push</code>:</p><p><strong>Web — instant.</strong> Vercel auto-deploys on every push to <code>main</code>. The next time a user refreshes the page, they are on the new version. No user action required, no install, no review. This is the fastest feedback loop in the stack and a real product-velocity advantage.</p><p><strong>iOS via TestFlight (beta path, immediate next step).</strong> When a new build is uploaded to App Store Connect, Apple performs a brief review — minutes to hours for an existing external tester group, and 24–48 hours for the first build to a new external group. Once approved, the TestFlight app on the tester's iPhone or iPad shows the new build as available. The tester taps \"Update,\" or has auto-install enabled and gets it in the background. <em>The friction is on the developer side</em> (Xcode archive + upload), not the user side.</p><p><strong>iOS via App Store (production path, post-launch).</strong> Same friction asymmetry as TestFlight. The developer submits, Apple reviews for 24–48 hours, and the update appears in the App Store. Users with auto-updates enabled (most of them) get it in the background overnight. Users without auto-updates see an update badge on the App Store icon and tap \"Update.\"</p><p><strong>macOS desktop (Electron) — automatic, shipped at launch (2026-06-06).</strong> The desktop app integrates <code>electron-updater</code> so users no longer have to download fresh DMGs manually. After launch the app waits 8 seconds (so it doesn't compete with startup work), then silently checks an update feed hosted on the marketing site at <code>https://www.2ndbrainware.com/updates/mac/latest.yml</code>. If a newer version is published, electron-updater downloads it in the background while the user keeps working. When the download completes, a thin non-intrusive banner appears at the very top of the app shell: <em>\"Update ready. Version X.Y.Z is ready. Restart to apply.\"</em> with two buttons: <strong>Restart now</strong> (applies immediately) and <strong>Later</strong> (snoozes for 24 hours, reappears next launch). The banner is NOT a modal — the user keeps working uninterrupted if they pick Later. While the app stays open, it re-checks the feed every 4 hours. Users can also force a check on demand via Help menu &gt; <em>\"Check for Updates…\"</em>, which surfaces a toast (\"You're on the latest version\" or kicks off the silent download).</p><p><strong>Dev-mode skip:</strong> The updater is registered only when <code>app.isPackaged === true</code>. In dev mode (<code>npm run electron:dev</code>) the registration is skipped with a log line — trying to update a dev build produces confusing errors and there's nothing to update anyway. The renderer-side banner also no-ops outside Electron, so the web and iOS builds carry zero auto-updater code at runtime.</p><p><strong>Code-signing dependency.</strong> macOS Gatekeeper requires the DMG to be code-signed with a Developer ID Application certificate, and electron-updater verifies the signature before applying the update. Howard's Apple Developer cert + electron-builder publish config + the actual DMG upload step are on his external punch list — the code-side integration ships now, the production update feed goes live the moment those externals are wired.</p><p><strong>Windows / Linux desktop — not yet distributed.</strong> Build configs are ready but no MSI/AppImage is published. When they ship, the same <code>electron-updater</code> pattern applies with zero code changes — Windows and Linux are first-class targets of that library and the same generic publish provider already configured in <code>package.json</code> works for all three platforms.</p><p><strong>The shape of the asymmetry now.</strong> With the desktop auto-updater shipped, every actively-distributed platform is at \"updates happen in the background.\" Web is instant. iOS rides Apple's auto-updates. macOS desktop polls every 4 hours and surfaces a single-click Restart. The launch-quality gap that used to live in the Mac path is closed.</p>",
      "type": "standard",
      "parentId": "tech-stack-platform-strategy-2026-06-06",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": null
    },
    "5b35f388-dd86-4459-aa4c-4c15b6e8522e": {
      "id": "5b35f388-dd86-4459-aa4c-4c15b6e8522e",
      "name": "Beta-applicant approval flow (2026-06-10)",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "type": "default",
      "content": "IdiamPro is in invite-only beta. Every prospective user fills out a one-page application; Howard reviews each one personally and approves people one at a time. This section explains how the approval flow is wired together.\n\nTHE APPLICATION FORM (/signup)\n- Three fields: full name, email, and an optional \"What brings you to IdiamPro?\" textarea.\n- Submitting POSTs to /api/applicants/apply. The server adds a record to the local applicant store (a JSON file at .idiampro/applicants.json — same pattern as the unsubscribe store), captures IP + referrer from request headers, and fires off a notification email to howard@2ndbrainware.com with a deep link to /admin/applicants?focus=[id].\n- The user lands on a confirmation screen: \"Thanks — Howard reviews every beta application personally. You'll get an email when you're approved.\"\n- If the email is already on the allowlist (either via the INVITE_ALLOWLIST env var or because Howard has previously approved them), the form skips straight to Clerk's sign-up step instead.\n\nHOWARD'S DASHBOARD (/admin/applicants)\n- Three sections: Pending Applicants (Approve / Reject buttons next to each row), Approved Users (running list of every approved beta user with a mailto button + a private-notes textarea), Rejected (a quiet collapsed list for reference).\n- Search bar filters both lists by name or email. Time-window chips: All / This week / This month. CSV export buttons on both lists so Howard can pull his contact list any time.\n- Gate: same localStorage isAdmin === 'true' pattern as /admin/metrics and /admin/invites. The page sends an x-idiampro-admin: true header on every API call; server endpoints check the header.\n\nAPPROVAL ACTION\n- Clicking Approve flips the applicant's status to \"approved\", stamps the approval date, and triggers the \"You're in\" email.\n- The email is sent FROM \"Howard at IdiamPro <howard@2ndbrainware.com>\" with Reply-To set to howard@2ndbrainware.com — so hitting Reply lands in his inbox rather than a noreply alias. Copy is conversational: \"Your beta access is active. Sign in at [link]. Reply to this email if you have questions — Howard reads every one.\"\n- Approving an applicant ALSO adds their email to the dynamic allowlist with no redeploy needed.\n\nENFORCEMENT — THREE LAYERS OF DEFENSE\n- AppGate (src/components/app-gate.tsx) wraps every /app subroute. Signed-out users get redirected to /signup. Signed-in-but-not-approved users get redirected to /waiting (a friendly \"your application is in the queue\" page with a sign-out option for wrong-account cases).\n- The Clerk user.created webhook re-runs the allowlist check via isEmailAllowedAsync and deletes the Clerk account if the email isn't approved — BEFORE sending any welcome email.\n- The pre-signup /api/invite-check endpoint stays as the fast-path check used by /signup itself.\n\nTHE ALLOWLIST — TWO SOURCES UNIONED\n- INVITE_ALLOWLIST env var: comma-separated emails Howard pre-seeded (his own addresses, founding testers).\n- The applicant store: every email Howard has clicked \"Approve\" on.\n- src/lib/access/allowlist.ts exposes isEmailAllowedAsync() and getAllowedEmailsAsync() that union both sources. Stub-safe: if both sources are empty, every email is allowed (dev / local mode), same env-gated philosophy as the rest of IdiamPro.\n\nWHAT THE HOME PAGE CHANGED\n- The marketing page's top-nav and mobile-menu \"Launch App\" buttons no longer link directly to /app. They now split: signed-out shows \"Sign up free\" pointing to /signup; signed-in shows \"Open IdiamPro\" pointing to /app. The intentional hero CTA pair was already correct and is unchanged.\n- The /beta legacy page's success-screen and footer links to /app were also removed — they now route to / and /signup respectively."
    },
    "beta-feedback-form-2026-06-10": {
      "id": "beta-feedback-form-2026-06-10",
      "name": "Beta feedback form + 1-year Pro reward (2026-06-10)",
      "content": "<p>How the beta-feedback flow is wired together:</p><ul><li><strong>/feedback</strong> — a public page with a structured form. Top-line NPS + overall stars, a row per killer feature (labels pulled verbatim from the marketing site), open-ended &quot;best&quot; / &quot;biggest wish&quot; questions, workflow context, optional testimonial consent with attribution choice + photo/video upload, friction question, follow-up consent checkbox.</li><li><strong>/api/feedback/submit</strong> — the server route that persists the submission to <code>.idiampro/feedback.json</code> (same atomic-write JSON pattern as the applicant store and unsubscribe store), issues a 1-year Pro grant (writing both a local mirror and best-effort Clerk publicMetadata: <code>pro_until</code>, <code>pro_via</code>, <code>testimonial_consent</code>, <code>founding_user</code>), and emails Howard a structured summary via Resend.</li><li><strong>The reward</strong> — submitting earns 1 year of Pro features at no charge (set deliberately rather than lifetime, so the grant has a renewable conversation point). AI runs against the user's own API key (BYOK on API), so usage cost stays with the user. Sharing a video testimonial flips the user's <code>founding_user</code> flag, which the app reads to render a Founding User badge.</li><li><strong>The 14-day reminder</strong> — a Vercel cron job at <code>/api/cron/feedback-reminder</code> runs daily at noon Pacific (20:00 UTC). It walks every approved applicant, finds the ones who are 14-90 days past approval, haven't submitted feedback, and haven't been reminded yet. Sends them a personal-toned email from Howard inviting them to the form. The applicant record gains a <code>feedbackReminderSentAt</code> timestamp so we never double-send.</li><li><strong>/admin/feedback</strong> — a sibling of /admin/applicants gated by the same <code>localStorage.isAdmin === 'true'</code> v1 trust contract. Lists every submission with NPS + stars + feature summary, filter chips (All / Testimonial-consented / Public-quotable / Video), search, and a CSV export button.</li><li><strong>Welcome email extension</strong> — the welcome email Howard sends on approval already mentioned what to expect from the beta. It now also includes a paragraph telegraphing the upcoming feedback ask in abstract terms (&quot;around the two-week mark&quot;), so the reward isn't a surprise when the cron fires.</li><li><strong>In-app entry point</strong> — a Help/overflow menu item labelled &quot;Share feedback&quot; opens /feedback in a new tab so beta users always have a permanent way back to the form.</li></ul>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": []
    },
    "f79853c1-2d2b-43f9-aba6-fa9c2ffc718e": {
      "id": "f79853c1-2d2b-43f9-aba6-fa9c2ffc718e",
      "name": "Unified Cmd+Z (undo across content + structure + AI transforms)",
      "content": "Whenever you do anything that changes the outline (typing, adding or deleting items, moving things around, pasting, applying an AI transform like Reformat or Translate or Refresh from Web, or importing), the app takes a snapshot of the entire outline state and pushes it onto an in-memory undo stack. There's no hard cap on depth — you can undo dozens or hundreds of steps back as long as the session memory holds.\n\nWhen you press Cmd+Z (or Cmd+Shift+Z to redo), the app pops the top of the stack and restores it. Big actions (AI transforms, imports, multi-item deletes) carry a friendly label like 'Translate Outline' or 'Delete 5 items'. The undo shows a persistent toast 'Undid: [label]' so you can see exactly what reverted. Small things like single-character typing stay quiet so toasts don't pile up while you write.\n\nTiptap (the rich-text editor inside each node) keeps its own character-level undo too — while you're focused inside a node, Cmd+Z undoes one character at a time inside that node, the way you'd expect. When the editor is empty or you've moved focus elsewhere, Cmd+Z falls through to the outline-level undo and reverts the bigger action.",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": true,
      "createdAt": 1781154318802,
      "updatedAt": 1781154318802
    },
    "howitworks-backup-restore-2026-06-10": {
      "id": "howitworks-backup-restore-2026-06-10",
      "name": "Backup / Restore + Auto-Snapshots",
      "content": "<p>How the explicit Backup / Restore feature is built (shipped 2026-06-10).</p><p><strong>Why this exists separately from the legacy auto-backup-on-save:</strong> The throttled save-time backup runs in the background and you can&apos;t see it. The new explicit feature gives users a button in the toolbar — they can take a snapshot whenever they want, see the list, preview before restoring, and roll back. It also automatically protects them from accidental AI-transform damage and self-inflicted Restore mistakes.</p><p><strong>Where snapshots live:</strong></p><ul><li>Folder structure: [outlines folder] / .backups / [safe-outline-name] / [stamp]-[label].idm</li><li>Each snapshot is a complete JSON dump of the outline at that moment — identical shape to the .idm file the app loads on startup.</li><li>A sibling [stamp]-[label].idm.meta.json holds the original (unsanitized) label and the kind tag (manual / auto-transform / auto-restore).</li></ul><p><strong>Three trigger paths:</strong></p><ol><li><strong>Manual</strong> — user clicks the shield button in the outline toolbar, optionally types a label, clicks Back up now. The dialog writes the snapshot and shows a persistent confirmation toast.</li><li><strong>Auto before AI transform</strong> — every AI transform&apos;s apply handler (Reformat, Translate, Transform Outline, Refresh from Web) calls snapshotBeforeTransform() before mutating the outline. Fire-and-forget — never blocks the apply. Skipped when the user has opted out in Settings.</li><li><strong>Auto before Restore</strong> — when the user restores a snapshot, the dialog first writes a snapshot of the CURRENT state labeled &quot;auto: before restore&quot;, then loads the chosen snapshot&apos;s content over the outline.</li></ol><p><strong>How the IPC works:</strong></p><ul><li>The renderer never touches the filesystem directly. It calls electronAPI.snapshotCreate / snapshotList / snapshotRead / snapshotDelete / snapshotShowFolder.</li><li>The main process handles every IPC call, with path-traversal validation on every file read or write.</li><li>Web builds detect the missing IPC bridge and silently no-op (snapshots are desktop-only for now). The toolbar button still appears so the UX is consistent, but the dialog shows an amber notice explaining the limitation.</li></ul><p><strong>Retention enforcement:</strong> The 20-snapshot cap is enforced server-side (Electron main) — every snapshot-create call runs pruneSnapshotsForOutline() which sorts the .idm files by their timestamp prefix and deletes anything beyond the cap.</p><p><strong>Where it fits the three-layer data protection model:</strong></p><ul><li>Layer 1 (Cmd+Z, in-memory) — protects against the user clicking something wrong.</li><li>Layer 2 (this feature, disk snapshots) — protects when Cmd+Z isn&apos;t enough: app crashed, undo stack overflowed, the user took a destructive action and dismissed it through a confirmation.</li><li>Layer 3 (derivative-by-default for content-altering AI transforms, coming next) — protects by default rather than by user opt-in.</li></ul>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "data-storage",
      "childrenIds": []
    },
    "howitworks-derivative-outlines-2026-06-10": {
      "id": "howitworks-derivative-outlines-2026-06-10",
      "name": "Derivative Outlines (the third protective layer)",
      "content": "<p>How the derivative-outline feature is built (shipped 2026-06-10). The third protective layer in the outline-data protection model.</p><p><strong>Why this exists:</strong> An outline can represent years of a user's intellectual work. Cmd+Z protects against the user clicking something wrong (Layer 1). Disk snapshots protect when Cmd+Z isn't enough — app crashed, undo stack overflowed (Layer 2). Derivative-by-default protects BY DEFAULT: when an AI transform rewrites an outline, the safer path is to create a NEW outline rather than overwrite the original. The user has to explicitly opt in to in-place modification.</p><p><strong>The two-field data model extension:</strong></p><ul><li><code>derivedFromOutlineId</code> — string, optional. The ID of the parent outline this was derived from.</li><li><code>derivationLabel</code> — string, optional. A short hint at how it was derived (e.g. \"Middle School Version\", \"Refreshed 2026-06-10\").</li></ul><p>Both fields are optional and backward-compatible — outlines saved before this feature simply omit them and load fine.</p><p><strong>The shared dialog UI:</strong> A small reusable component (<code>derivation-choice.tsx</code>) renders the radio + editable label-suffix field, used by all four transform dialogs (Transform Outline, Reformat, Refresh from Web, Translate). Each dialog passes a unique <code>idPrefix</code> so the radio/label IDs don't collide in the DOM when multiple dialogs are mounted in the React tree.</p><p><strong>Default mode per transform:</strong></p><ul><li>Transform Outline → <strong>derivative</strong> (the transform rewrites STRUCTURE — safer to fork).</li><li>Reformat (whole node) → <strong>derivative</strong>. Selection-scope reformat is always in-place — a partial-selection derivative would be incoherent.</li><li>Refresh from Web → <strong>derivative</strong> (brings in NEW content from the web).</li><li>Translate → <strong>in-place</strong> (the user already chose the target language and expects replacement). Derivative is offered as opt-in.</li></ul><p><strong>The auto-suggest label helper:</strong> <code>src/lib/derivation/label-from-prompt.ts</code> exposes <code>suggestDerivationLabel(promptText)</code> — pure string manipulation, no AI call. It strips leading filler verbs (\"rewrite\", \"make it\", \"convert to\"), takes the first 4-6 meaningful words, title-cases if the original was lowercase, and appends \"Version\" unless the phrase already ends in a standalone noun like \"Summary\" / \"Outline\". Two siblings (<code>suggestRefreshLabel</code>, <code>suggestTranslateLabel</code>) handle the date-stamped Refresh and language-prefixed Translate cases.</p><p><strong>The derivative builder:</strong> <code>src/lib/derivation/build-derivative.ts</code> exposes <code>buildDerivativeOutline()</code>. Given the original outline + the transformed node map + a label, it produces a fresh Outline with a new UUID, a name of \"[Original] — [Label]\", a deep clone of the node map (so the original is never mutated), and the two metadata fields populated. Sibling helpers (<code>cloneNodesWithSingleContent</code>, <code>deepCloneNodes</code>) cover the single-node-content (Reformat) and whole-map (LIVE BOOKS / Translate) cases.</p><p><strong>The parent apply handlers branch on derivation:</strong> Each of the four apply handlers in <code>outline-pro.tsx</code> (handleApplyTransformOutline, handleApplyReformat, handleApplyLiveBooks, handleApplyTranslate) inspects the optional <code>derivation</code> argument. When mode === 'derivative' the handler builds a new Outline, appends it to the <code>outlines</code> array, and switches the current outline ID to the new one — the original is untouched on disk and in memory. When mode === 'inplace' (or the field is absent) it runs the pre-existing in-place path, which still fires the auto-snapshot before mutating.</p><p><strong>Sidebar nesting:</strong> The existing parent-to-children map in <code>sidebar-pane.tsx</code> (originally built for cross-outline-link nesting) was extended to also index derivatives by their <code>derivedFromOutlineId</code>. Derivatives are filtered out of the top-level list (they render nested under the parent instead). The icon switches from FileText to a purple GitFork badge; hovering shows the derivation label. If the parent is deleted, derivatives orphan gracefully — they remain in the library at top-level with a muted \"(orphan derivative)\" hint.</p><p><strong>The \"Derived from\" banner:</strong> A small chip in <code>outline-pane.tsx</code>, shown between the title row and the toolbar. Reads \"Derived from [Parent name] · [Derivation label]\" with an \"Open original\" button. If the parent has been deleted, shows \"Original was deleted\" instead.</p><p><strong>Multi-level derivation:</strong> A derivative of a derivative has its own <code>derivedFromOutlineId</code> pointing at its parent derivative. The sidebar's recursive OutlineRow render renders the chain naturally as grandchildren.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "data-storage",
      "childrenIds": []
    },
    "multimedia-ai-2026-06-11": {
      "id": "multimedia-ai-2026-06-11",
      "name": "Multimedia AI — Capture from image + Share as YouTube package (2026-06-11)",
      "content": "<p><strong>What it is.</strong> Two new capabilities ship together because both leverage Gemini's multimedia API and both follow the existing preview-and-approve transform engine pattern: <em>Capture from image</em> (image-to-outline) and <em>Share as YouTube package</em> (outline-to-YouTube).</p><p><strong>Capture from image.</strong> The user picks (or, on iOS/Android, captures with the device camera) an image — whiteboard photo, hand-drawn mind map, sticky-note board, slide screenshot. The image is sent to the new <code>imageToOutlineAction</code> server action which calls Gemini with a vision prompt asking for a structured JSON tree. The response is shape-validated and surfaced in the <code>ImageToOutlineDialog</code> — a three-panel preview (source thumbnail, editable proposed outline tree, where it lands). On Apply the new <code>insertProposedNodes</code> helper appends the proposed nodes as children of the selected node, recalculates prefixes, and tags each new node's metadata with a <code>sourceImageId</code>. The source image bytes are persisted to localStorage in v1 (key <code>idiampro:sourceImage:&lt;id&gt;</code>) so the UI can render a thumbnail next to the parent node and the user can always see what generated the content. The three data-protection layers are honored: an auto-snapshot is written via <code>snapshotBeforeTransform</code> before insertion, <code>markNextAction</code> registers a single Cmd+Z step, and the dialog offers a 'Save as new outline' opt-in that routes through <code>buildDerivativeOutline</code>.</p><p><strong>Share as YouTube package.</strong> The user right-clicks or picks 'Share as YouTube package' from the Export menu against a chapter (a selected node + descendants). The <code>YoutubePackageDialog</code> asks for duration (60s / 90s / 2min / 5min), style (Tutorial / Explainer / Promo / Story), and an optional audience hint. The new <code>generateYoutubePackageAction</code> server action sends the chapter's plain-text contents (via the <code>nodeSubtreeToText</code> helper) plus the user's options to Gemini, which returns a structured JSON object with 8 outputs: voiceover script (with [shot N] markers and timing cues), chapter list, 200-300 word description, 5 title variants, 15-20 SEO tags, thumbnail concept, B-roll prompts (for Runway/MagicLight/Sora), and a screen-recording shot list. Each output is shown in its own editable tab; the user can edit any field inline. Export options: download as a single markdown file (assembled by <code>packageToMarkdown</code>), or 'Save as new outline' (creates a derivative with one node per output).</p><p><strong>Files.</strong></p><ul><li><p><code>src/app/actions.ts</code> — new <code>imageToOutlineAction</code> and <code>generateYoutubePackageAction</code> server actions; both use the existing <code>GoogleGenAI</code> client and the default Gemini model.</p></li><li><p><code>src/lib/multimedia/insert-proposed-nodes.ts</code> — <code>insertProposedNodes</code> (renderer-side NodeMap append) and <code>nodeSubtreeToText</code> (chapter context dump).</p></li><li><p><code>src/components/image-to-outline-dialog.tsx</code> — pick/run/preview phases, three-panel preview, inline rename/delete on proposed nodes, DerivationChoice wiring.</p></li><li><p><code>src/components/youtube-package-dialog.tsx</code> — configure/run/preview phases, 8-tab editable output, markdown export, save-as-outline.</p></li><li><p><code>src/components/outline-pro.tsx</code> — state + handlers (<code>handleApplyImageToOutline</code>, <code>handleExportYoutubeMarkdown</code>, <code>handleSaveYoutubeAsOutline</code>), wired through to both render passes.</p></li><li><p><code>src/components/ai-menu.tsx</code> — 'Capture from image' Smart Tools entry (visible when a node is selected).</p></li><li><p><code>src/components/outline-pane.tsx</code> — 'Share as YouTube package' entry in the Export menu.</p></li><li><p><code>src/lib/use-ai-usage-gate.tsx</code> — new <code>imageToOutline</code> and <code>youtubePackage</code> feature keys for the AI usage gate.</p></li></ul><p><strong>iOS.</strong> The 'Take photo' button in the Capture-from-image dialog is rendered only on Capacitor iOS/Android (detected via <code>getPlatformContext().os</code>). It uses an HTML file input with <code>capture=\"environment\"</code>, which Capacitor's webview honors by opening the device camera. v1 deliberately does NOT pull in <code>@capacitor/camera</code> — the HTML capture attribute is sufficient and avoids a native-modules churn before launch. Future hardening: swap to <code>@capacitor/camera</code> for permission UX consistency with the rest of the Capacitor app.</p><p><strong>Provenance storage.</strong> Source images live in browser localStorage in v1 (capped at ~2.5MB per image). Future work: move to a <code>.media/&lt;outline-id&gt;/&lt;image-hash&gt;.png</code> folder next to the .idm file via Electron IPC so very large images don't bloat localStorage and so iOS keeps them in the document container.</p><p><strong>Settings.</strong> A 'Multimedia capture' section in Settings → Preferences carries two controls in the Phase-1 design: a toggle 'Save source images alongside outline' (ON by default — preserves provenance) and a provider dropdown 'Image-to-outline AI provider' defaulting to Gemini. Both are forward-looking — the provider dropdown is single-option in v1 but the action signature accepts a provider arg so swapping in Claude Vision or other models is a one-file change.</p>",
      "type": "document",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": ""
    },
    "email-system-plain-english-2026-06-11": {
      "id": "email-system-plain-english-2026-06-11",
      "name": "Email System — Plain English",
      "content": "<p><strong>How the email system works (plain English):</strong></p><p><strong>The five pieces:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>2ndbrainware.com</strong> — your domain name. The street address of your business on the internet.</li><li><strong>Namecheap</strong> — where you bought the domain. Also where you control its \"phone book\" — the DNS — which tells the rest of the world where your website lives and where your email lives.</li><li><strong>Vercel</strong> — the company that runs your website's computers. When someone types 2ndbrainware.com, Vercel hands them the page.</li><li><strong>PrivateEmail</strong> — your business mailbox. Think of it as a P.O. box at Namecheap that receives mail addressed to howard@2ndbrainware.com.</li><li><strong>Upstash</strong> — a tiny database that remembers who applied to your beta. Like a notebook that's always synced.</li></ul><p><strong>What happens when someone signs up:</strong></p><ol><li>They visit <strong>2ndbrainware.com</strong> in their browser. Vercel sends them the marketing page.</li><li>They fill out the signup form (name, email, \"what brings you here\") and click submit.</li><li>A small program on Vercel catches the form data. It does two things in order: writes the applicant's name and email into <strong>Upstash</strong> (so you have a permanent record), then it tells <strong>PrivateEmail</strong> (through a behind-the-scenes service called SMTP — basically the email pipeline) to send YOU a notification email.</li><li>PrivateEmail delivers the email to <strong>howard@2ndbrainware.com</strong>. It arrives in your mailbox within seconds.</li><li>You open the mailbox (via the webmail shortcut on your Desktop) and see who applied.</li></ol><p><strong>The same pieces handle approval too:</strong> when you click \"Approve\" in the admin dashboard, Vercel asks PrivateEmail to send the new user a \"welcome to the beta\" email. Same path.</p><p>Five companies, three for the website + one for the mailbox + one for the database. Each does one thing.</p><p><strong>Set up 2026-06-11</strong> during a single working session including: pointing 2ndbrainware.com DNS at Vercel, configuring PrivateEmail MX records via Namecheap's MAIL SETTINGS, provisioning Upstash KV in Vercel's Storage tab, swapping the email sender from Resend to PrivateEmail SMTP via nodemailer, and migrating file-based JSON storage to Upstash KV.</p>",
      "type": "chapter",
      "parentId": "root",
      "childrenIds": [],
      "isCollapsed": false,
      "prefix": ""
    },
